StarryNite/Acetree are cell tracking and lineage editing tools used primarily, though not solely in the C. elegans community to trace and interact with embryonic cell lineages. Developed by Zhirong Bao while a postdoc in Bob Waterston’s lab at the University of Washington the software has been used, maintained and updated for around 15 years with efforts focussed at MSKCC for the past decade. It is the dominant tool for cell tracking in the C. elegans embryo and regularly used in around a dozen labs in support of projects like dynamic single cell gene expression and the WormGUIDES neuronal outgrowth atlas. 

StarryNite, written in Matlab, provides tracking for fluorescently labeled nuclei.  Tracking combines image processing and classical machine learning to provide high accuracy on dense cells in limited (axially and laterally) resolution images. Acetree is a Java-based interface for curating and exploring results superimposed over images or as an abstract 3D model with detailed control over model coloration. It includes tools for editing, bookmarking and annotating events. Both tools will work with arbitrary data, but provide logic for automatically assigning canonical C. elegans names to cells and a variety of other convenient features for navigating C. elegans embryos.

Apache Airavata is software that enables the secure access to and management of scientific software and data on remote, distributed computing infrastructure in support of reproducible research for communities of users. Apache Airavata’s core concept is support for multiple science gateway tenants, in which each tenant represents a community of researchers who wish to securely access a collection of scientific applications and data to perform online computational experiments, sharing results with collaborators. Administrators for each science gateway tenant manage their own user bases, software applications, and computing resources. Apache Airavata middleware is built as a set of distributed components (or microservices) interacting through well-defined programming interfaces and message formats. This approach allows Apache Airavata to integrate best of breed software, either developed by the project or implemented by integrating third party open source software, for its core services such as metadata capture, workflow execution, data movement, and user management. Apache Airavata services are accessed by a tenant (client) through a well-defined, programming language-independent application programming interface. Typical science gateway tenants have Web-based user environments but desktop clients and other endpoints are also supported.

We present *AMARETTO as a software toolbox for network biology and medicine, towards developing a data-driven platform for diagnostic, prognostic and therapeutic decision-making in complex diseases. *AMARETTO links diseases, drivers, targets and drugs via network graph-based fusion of multi-omics, clinical, imaging, and driver and drug perturbation data across model systems and patient studies of complex diseases.

The *AMARETTO platform features a modular approach to incorporating prior biological knowledge based on multimodal and multiscale network-structured modeling: (1) AMARETTO learns networks of regulatory circuits - circuits of drivers and target genes - from functional genomics or multi-omics data and associates these circuits to clinical, molecular and imaging-derived phenotypes within each biological system (e.g., model systems or patients); (2) Community-AMARETTO learns subnetworks of regulatory circuits that are shared or distinct across networks derived from multiple biological systems (e.g., model systems and patients, cohorts and individuals, diseases and etiologies, in vitro and in vivo systems); (3) Perturbation-AMARETTO maps genetic and chemical perturbations in model systems onto patient-derived multi-omics networks for driver and drug discovery, respectively, and prioritizes lead drivers, targets and drugs for follow-up with experimental validation; (4) Imaging-AMARETTO maps radiographic and histopathology imaging data onto the patient-derived multi-omics networks for non-invasive and histopathology imaging diagnostics.

This project is aimed at expanding the AOmontaging alignment tool into a multi-modal retinal imaging application. The goal of this project is to allow additional retinal imaging modalities (color fundus photography [CFP] and optical coherence tomography [OCT]) to be placed into the coordinate frame defined by the adaptive optics scanning laser ophthalmoscope (AOSLO) montage. These additional modalities will allow researchers to analyze spatially coherent multi-variate imaging measures derived from the distinct information provided by the different modalities.  

This project will consist of three main stages.
1.) Alignment of the AOSLO montages generated by the AOmontaging with CFP images using vessel features extracted from both images. 
2.) Alignment of the OCT image with the CFP by aligning the OCT-SLO image with the fundus image.  
3.) Conversion of the original AOmontaging codebase into Python to allow for non-proprietary open source support and development. 

Successful implementation of this project will result in a tool that can take in images from all three imaging modalities of a single subject and spatially align the images across modalities. This will enable multi-modal analysis of retinal features.

The Apollo genome annotation editor is a tool for the manual editing and revision of genome annotations. Genomics relies on high-quality sequenced genomes with well-curated annotations for the locations and structure of genes, regulatory elements, transposons, and other relevant features of interest. Improving the accuracy of genome annotation is a complex and iterative process requiring researchers to review and incorporate multiple sources of information such as transcriptome alignments, predictive models based on sequence profiles, and comparisons to features found in related organisms.

Apollo uses a web-based graphical user interface based on a genome browser. Curators can drag gene models to edit their structure. It is somewhat similar to Google Docs in that edits to a gene model show up "live" in all users' browsers.

Increasingly Apollo has been used as a crowdsourcing-style tool, aimed at expert members of a community who wish to contribute to the review and improvement of their organism's annotations.

Apollo has seen several shifts in the way genome projects are handled: the "model organism" era, the comparative genomics era, the era of personal genomes. The next will be the era of high-volume human and phylogenetic sequencing.

The app is built for iOS (phone & tablet). It contains data for ~1400 approved drug structures, along with accompanying metadata. It presents an interactive browser for viewing and searching. The product (version 1) is written in Objective-C, and will be deprecated as soon as the new version is ready. Its replacement will be an open source project hosted in a public GitHub repository with a permissive license. The community will be invited to review and contribute to the data content, as mistakes are found and as new drugs are approved (or un-approved). The main browsing code will be rewritten in TypeScript (which cross-compiles to JavaScript) and the bulk of it will be platform neutral. It will be deployed for pure web, desktop (via Electron) and iOS + Android each with a custom wrapper. These deployed versions of the tool will be made available for download, browsing or installation from the corresponding app hosting service, open and free of charge.

SCENIC (Single-CEll regulatory Network Inference and Clustering) enables biologists to infer transcription factors, gene regulatory networks and cell types from single-cell RNA-seq data. Available as R/Bioconductor package and Python package. Also available as workflow (Nextflow). Depends on "cisTarget databases", which are currently available at https://resources.aertslab.org/cistarget/.

For the analysis of single-cell ATAC-seq data, using probabilistic topic modeling, we have developed cisTopic, available at https://github.com/aertslab/cistopic.

We are proposing the development of an open-source augmented reality (AR) experience for patients using a rehabilitation robot.  This project will be conducted at the Rehabilitation Institute at Loma Linda University Health, where patients with stroke are currently treated with medical robots to improve their motor function of their impaired upper extremities.
rg_name: Augmented Reality Interface for Users of a Rehabilitation Robot

description: Apache Arrow is a cross-language development platform for in-memory data. It specifies a standardized language-independent columnar memory format for flat and hierarchical data, organized for efficient analytic operations on modern hardware. It provides computational libraries, conversion between the most common file formats (CSV, JSON, Parquet, ORC, Avro), zero-copy streaming messaging, and interprocess communication. Languages currently supported include C, C++, C#, Go, Java, JavaScript, MATLAB, Python, R, Ruby, and Rust.

ASAP is a web-based portal enabling the interactive analysis of any type of (sc)RNA-seq dataset (10x H5, Loom, Text) and providing a comprehensive list of tools which guides the user through the different steps of the analysis pipeline: from Filtering, Normalization, Dimension Reduction, Clustering, Differential Gene Expression, to Functional Enrichment. ASAP received a “Collaborative Computational Tool” CZI grant, enabling the users to fetch Loom files directly from the HCA DCP API and to study/analyze the HCA datasets directly within the ASAP environment. ASAP currently hosts ~2500 projects and to keep its status as a leading (sc)RNA-seq analysis portal, we will further enhance it by 1) upgrading the metadata structure, and providing tools/plots for displaying them and analyzing their distributions with various embedded QCs, 2) improving ASAP’s application to biomedical/clinical research through the addition of databases to explore functional enrichment of cell type-specific genes (OncoDB, OMIM, DrugBank), and through a more automated way of annotating cell clusters using tools such as scMAP or Garnett, and 3) adding a “merging” feature, to merge projects with HCA datasets or any other ASAP project. This later feature will include batch effect correction tools such as Combat, MNN or scMerge for making the datasets comparable.

ASPIRE is an open-source software package for processing single-particle cryo-EM data to determine three-dimensional structures of biological macromolecules. The package includes advanced algorithms based on rigorous mathematics and recent developments in statistics and machine learning. It provides unique and improved solutions to important computational challenges of the cryo-EM processing pipeline, including 3-D ab-initio modeling, 2-D class averaging, automatic particle picking, and 3-D heterogeneity analysis. ASPIRE was originally developed in MATLAB, but to increase usability and portability, most of it has been recently ported to Python. Moving forward, the Python version will supersede the MATLAB one. Development is led by Amit Singer at Princeton University in collaboration with Yoel Shkolnisky at Tel-Aviv University. Singer and Shkolnisky started researching mathematical aspects of cryo-EM in 2007 as Gibbs Assistant Professors at Yale University.  ASPIRE came about as the initial software implementation of various new algorithms resulting from their collaboration. Over the years, it has added more computational tools based on the research of postdocs and students. The project has now grown to the point where maintenance and development require the effort of software engineers. Their help will enable the novel mathematical tools introduced by ASPIRE to make a high impact on structural biology.

Phylogenies are trees that show evolutionary relationships between species and are nowadays mostly inferred from genomic data. A major challenge in the statistical inference of phylogenies is the potential for discordance between phylogenies of individual genes. ASTRAL is a tool for inferring a species-level phylogeny given gene-level phylogenies. Given a set of input "gene trees", ASTRAL outputs a "species tree". Its algorithm enjoys statistical guarantees of consistency under specific models of genome evolution and the method grows polynomially with the size of the input dataset (worst-case sub-cubically, and close to quadratically in practice). 

ASTRAL has had high accuracy and good running time in simulation and biological analyses. As a result, it has become the dominant method in the field. Its large user base has motivated us to develop several versions of the algorithm (currently, ASTRAL-III), to constantly add new features, and to improve its scalability using things like parallelism, vectorization, and randomization. 

Despite the large user base and constant algorithmic improvement, a very small team has been working on developing and maintaining the codebase. Also, the code is old and can benefit from major refactoring.

ATLAS is a free, publicly available, web based, open source software created by OHDSI. It is intended to provide a unified interface to standardized patient-level data converted to the OMOP Common Data Model (CDM) and to conducting  observational research on them. Its GUI allows researches to define patient cohorts, select analytical designs, set parameters and executeanalytical methods against data.

The Odysseus team is an active OHDSI ATLAS and WebAPI developer and OHDSI contributor. Odysseus helps various Healthcare, Academic, Pharma, Payer and Government organizations to enable ATLAS in a secure Enterprise environment. 

The proposal is to ensure the sufficient funding of the development and maintenance activities to improve the quality, stability and functionality of the tool with a goal of expanding OHDSI ATLAS and other OHDSI open standards adoptions across Healthcare, Academic, Pharma, Payer and Government organizations and institutions throughout the world.

ATLAS is a free, publicly available web-based, open-source software application developed by the OHDSI community to support the design and execution of observational analyses to generate real world evidence from patient level observational data. ATLAS is an open science analytics platform that can be installed locally within any institution to perform analyses across one or more observational databases which have been standardized to the OMOP Common Data Model and can facilitate exchange of analysis designs with any other organizations across the OHDSI community who have adopted the same open science community standards and tools.

BAMnostic was written from the ground-up as a fully-featured, pure Python implementation of BAM file random access and parsing. Special care was taken to ensure BAMnostic had no dependencies outside of the Python standard library. As a corollary of the lack of dependencies, BAMnostic is not bound to a specific Python version (from 2.7 onward), or runtime (CPython and all stable versions of PyPy). Additionally, BAMnostic retains much of the same BAM file API as pysam. This allows BAMnostic to work as a drop-in replacement for pysam in everything from small web applications to full Python builds in Windows environments. As such, BAMnostic potentially makes genomic research and analytics available to a much greater software demographic.

Biological assays are an extremely important component of drug development, especially in defining and validating ligand/target interactions in early stage drug discovery efforts. High throughput assays have become extremely important in drug development efforts in both pharmaceutical and academic research settings due to the magnitude of relevant biological information that than be obtained from an experiment protocol (i.e. 10,000 to 100,000 compounds). With the primary goal of making data Findable, Accessible, Interoperable, Reusable (FAIR), we designed the first bioassay ontology to describe HTS experiments and screening results using expressive description logic. The BioAssay Ontology (BAO) describes biological screening assays and their results including high-throughput screening (HTS) data for the purpose of categorizing assays and data analysis. BAO is an extensible, knowledge-based, highly expressive (currently SHOIQ(D)) description of biological assays making use of descriptive logic based features of the Web Ontology Language (OWL). BAO currently has over 7000 classes, and also makes use of several other ontologies. This application proposes the creation of a BAO-core resource with BAO terminology that will be optimized and expanded with categories that will identify subtle assay nuances that may impact endpoint assay data, and provide a more user friendly resource for ontology naïve users.

The BasePlayer project was created for the urgent need for the efficient and versatile software, that could analyze massive sets of next-generation sequencing data and thus facilitate cancer genetics research. BasePlayer enables tightly integrated comparative variant analysis and visualization of thousands of NGS data samples and millions of variants, with numerous applications in disease, regulatory and population genomics. Although BasePlayer has been designed primarily for whole-genome and exome sequencing data, it is well-suited to various study settings, diseases and organisms by supporting standard and upcoming file formats.
rg_name: BasePlayer: versatile analysis software for large-scale genomic variant discovery

description: The Bioconductor mission is to promote the statistical analysis and comprehension of current and emerging high-throughput biological assays. Bioconductor is based on packages written primarily in the R programming language. Bioconductor is committed to open source, collaborative, distributed software development and literate, reproducible research. Enabling user and developer communities is an essential part of our mission. Scientific and Technical Advisory Boards provide project oversight.  The open source project defined in this proposal enhances the Bioconductor project by re-engineering the (currently bespoke) continuous integration and package distribution system to be more scalable, robust, maintainable, and independently deployable.  The build system is a fundamental vehicle for coordinating and improving the reliability of work of hundreds of developers of components of a widely used and interoperable genome analysis software ecosystem.  The work proposed here will yield benefits for multiple communities and large-scale projects such as Human Cell Atlas and NHGRI AnVIL, with which Bioconductor is already closely involved.

bcbio-nextgen is a python toolkit providing best-practice pipelines for fully automated high throughput sequencing analysis. The user writes a high level configuration file specifying inputs and analysis parameters which drives a parallel pipeline that handles distributed execution, idempotent processing restarts and safe transactional steps. The goal is to provide a shared community resource that automates the data processing component of sequencing analysis via validated, current, best-practice methods, providing researchers with more time to focus on the downstream biology. bcbio-nextgen is installable for users on any UNIX-based environment without administration privileges and installs all of the tools and data needed to run a wide variety of different NGS analyses. bcbio-nextgen is scalable and agnostic to the underlying compute infrastructure: it can run on a local machine, in HPC environments with support for all cluster schedulers and runs on cloud providers such as Amazon Web Services (AWS), Google Cloud (GCP) and Microsoft Azure.

This project will host the database of Bangladeshi reference genome constructed from the healthy individual as well as from individuals impacted by autism. This databased-oriented software will allow clinicians, parents and researchers to access the genetic variation that we observe within the population. This is extremely important for to implement precision medicine in Bangladesh and NeuroGen is the pioneer organization to do so. This project will enable precision diagnosis and early therapeutics by providing information regarding genetic mutations within the population.
rg_name: Bangladesh reference genome for genetic disorders

description: Collectively, the bedtools utilities are a swiss-army knife of tools for a wide-range of genomics analysis tasks. The most widely-used tools enable genome arithmetic: that is, set theory on the genome. For example, bedtools allows one to intersect, merge, count, complement, and shuffle genomic intervals from multiple files in widely-used genomic file formats such as BAM, BED, GFF/GTF, VCF. While each individual tool is designed to do a relatively simple task (e.g., intersect two interval files), quite sophisticated analyses can be conducted by combining multiple bedtools operations on the UNIX command line.

Our group has developed the open source Beiwe research platform for smartphone-based high-throughput digital phenotyping in biomedical research. The platform consists of the front-end smartphone applications for  iOS and Android devices. The back-end system, which supports a web-based study management portal and empowers data processing and storage through our Beiwe data analysis pipeline, makes use of Amazon Web Services (AWS) based cloud computing infrastructure. AWS makes it possible to offer Beiwe to the broadest possible research community and it enables its deployment essentially anywhere in the world to ensure compliance with regional regulation (e.g., such as GDPR in the European Union). Perhaps most importantly, the Beiwe platform consists of a growing suite of data analysis and modeling tools, the development of which is our main focus.

Bioinformatics software comes in a variety of programming languages and requires diverse installation methods. This heterogeneity makes management of a software stack complicated, error-prone, and inordinately time-consuming. Whereas software deployment has traditionally been handled by administrators, ensuring the reproducibility of data analyses1,2,3 requires that the researcher be able to maintain full control of the software environment, rapidly modify it without administrative privileges, and reproduce the same software stack on different machines.
The Conda package manager (https://conda.io) has become an increasingly popular means to overcome these challenges for all major operating systems. Conda allows defining software packages in terms of text-based recipes, which are compiled into relocatable binary packages which can be installed into isolated software environments without the need for administrative privileges.
The Bioconda project unlocks Conda’s strengths for bioinformatics, by providing thousands of Conda packages, covering almost all relevant bioinformatics tools. It has thereby become a backbone of reproducible data analysis in bioinformatics.

Bokeh is an interactive visualization library that targets modern web browsers for presentation. Its goal is to help scientists and data-scientists focus on their work, to create and share powerful visualizations of it, without having the distractions of unrelated "web tech".

Bokeh provides elegant, concise construction of versatile graphics, and extends this capability with high-performance interactivity over very large or streaming datasets. It natively supports tools for interactive drill-down and exploration: linked selections and ranges, hover inspectors, extensive UI event hooks, and sophisticated edit tools. It also provides a built-in set of widgets that can accompany plots. Most importantly, Bokeh affords the ability to connect these interactive presentations directly to all the powerful analytical tools available in Python in simple scripts. 

Bokeh can help anyone who would like to quickly and easily create interactive plots, dashboards, and data applications.

Standard software tools for data analysis (ImageJ, MATLAB, R, etc.) have contributed greatly to the progress of increasingly “data-rich” sciences. However, the equivalent standardized software tools for data acquisition are still lacking. Life science experiments demand a combination of multiple instrumentation and control technologies, in both physiology and behavior studies. The growing complexity on both the amount of data that is collected, and the rich conditions under which behavior must be explored, place increasing burdens on the experimenter to become a jack of all trades. Furthermore, the growing number of techniques and devices involved require experimental design to be iterated and tweaked multiple times.

Bonsai is a high-performance, easy to use, and flexible open-source visual programming language for acquiring and processing real-time data and composing the logic of experimental protocols. Bonsai allows integrating numerous streams of data in parallel and combining them using an event-based algebra expressed in a compact visual workflow. This language has allowed scientists with no previous programming experience to quickly develop their own custom data acquisition systems, being greatly adopted in neuroscience to monitor behavior and neural activity. Bonsai has recently expanded to other life sciences, public engagement and education, and the arts and sciences movement.

Clinical trial designs in the areas of oncology, rare disease, and pediatric care are generally limited by the number of patients that can be enrolled in a trial. Poor enrollment results in trials that do not reach definitive endpoints and must either be abandoned or decided upon despite uncertainty in their efficacy. Recent advances in the area of multisource-exchangeability models (MEMs) provide a mechanism for "borrowing" power from similar trials so that the information gained in one trial can be leveraged in an under enrolled trial. These techniques can be leveraged to more quickly drug efficacy and safety in several contexts. Some of these include understanding adverse event profiles for oncology patients taking cytotoxic drugs using historical data from similar cytotoxic drugs, understanding pediatric therapies based on historical data from equivalent adult trials, and dynamically declaring efficacy or futility in ongoing trials as new, relevant data becomes available. This project implements these MEM methodologies as a package for the R computing environment, providing easy-to-use analyses for determining the extent to which information can be shared between trials, providing trial analysis data relevant to go/no-go decisions, and visualizations to illustrate distributional and exchangeability relationships in clinical trial data.

breseq is a computational pipeline for finding mutations relative to a reference sequence in short-read DNA re-sequencing data. It is optimized for microbial genomes (<20 Mb). breseq is a command line tool implemented in C++ and R.

BWA is a software package for mapping DNA sequences against a large reference genome, such as the human genome. It consists of three algorithms: BWA-backtrack, BWA-SW and BWA- MEM. The first algorithm is designed for Illumina sequence reads up to 100bp, while the rest two for longer sequences ranged from 70bp to a few megabases. BWA-MEM and BWA-SW share similar features such as the support of long reads and chimeric alignment, but BWA-MEM, which is the latest, is generally recommended as it is faster and more accurate. BWA-MEM also has better performance than BWA-backtrack for 70-100bp Illumina reads.

CaImAn implements a set of essential methods required in the analysis pipeline of large scale calcium imaging data. Fast and scalable algorithms are implemented for motion correction, source extraction, spike deconvolution, and component registration across multiple days. It is suitable for both two-photon and one-photon fluorescence microscopy data, and can be run in both batch and online modes. CaImAn also contains some routines for the analysis of behavior from video cameras.

The Cancer Genome Interpreter (CGI) is an initiative that appeared in early 2018. Its main objective is to reduce the complexity which arises from the genome sequencing, creating an intuitive environment where clinicians and researchers can analyze patient’s genomic data. The analysis results in a list of genomic features with tumorigenic relevance and its associated biomarkers of response to anti-cancer treatments.

CATCH is a Python package for designing assays that enrich diverse nucleic acid sequence, enabling detection and sequencing of the many pathogens and other microbes present at low abundance in patient samples. CATCH accepts genomes encompassing all known genetic diversity of one or more microbial species, and designs probe sequences that guarantee coverage of this diversity. The output of CATCH are comprehensive and compact probe sets for nucleic acid capture and enrichment. CATCH can design with a specified constraint on the number of oligonucleotides (e.g., according to budget) by searching for the optimal design within the given limit. This makes CATCH’s designs scale well with genetic diversity and makes its designs cost-effective. CATCH is also flexible, supporting applications beyond genome enrichment, such as differential identification of species. CATCH has been used to design a probe set that enriches whole-genomes of all viruses known to infect humans, including all their strain diversity, among other probe sets. It is being used to design assays for other studies involving pathogen detection, microbial genome sequencing, and microbiome/virome characterization.
rg_name: CATCH (Compact Aggregation of Targets for Comprehensive Hybridization)

description: causalinfer is a generalized package for causal inference. This package is modeled after the infer R package, which does classical hypothesis testing in a more expressive form that other statistical modeling packages (e.g. a function `hypothesis()` that explicitly sets what you are testing). infer is also designed to be accessible and teachable. causalinfer will be the center point of the packages in this proposal: it will have verbs for setting assumptions, outcomes (what we are comparing), estimands (what estimate we are trying to measure, e.g. risk difference, odds ratio, etc), and more. This package will also lay the groundwork for two future packages: propensity, a toolkit for working with propensity scores, weighted models, and so on, and gmethods, a toolkit for specifying and working with G-methods, an important class of causal models.

The cBioPortal for Cancer Genomics is an open-access web resource and an open-source software platform that enables interactive, exploratory analysis of large-scale cancer genomics data sets. It integrates genomic and clinical data and provides a suite of visualization and analysis options, including cohort and patient-level visualization, mutation visualization, survival analysis, alteration enrichment analysis, and network analysis. The user-interface is user-friendly, responsive, and makes genomic data easily accessible to scientists and clinicians. The interface was explicitly built and continues to evolve with careful usability studies involving various types of users, and an active and engaged user base. Based on analysis of user traffic and citations, and comparison with other tools in the field, the cBioPortal is arguably the most feature-rich and widely used data mining platform in cancer genomics, and a unique resource for the entire cancer research community.

CDGnet is an evidence-based network approach for recommending targeted cancer therapies, available as a user-friendly informatics tool. Our approach can be used to expand the range of options of targeted therapies for cancer patients who undergo molecular profiling. It considers biological pathway information specifically by looking at downstream targets of oncogenes and is personalized for individual patients via the user-inputted molecular alterations and cancer type. CDGnet integrates disparate sources of knowledge and provides results in a number of easily-accessible and usable forms, while separating targeted cancer therapies into categories in an evidence-based manner.
rg_name: CDGnet: Therapy recommendations using biological networks

description: The UCSC TumorMap is a Google Maps-like browser to investigate large-scale cancer genomics datasets. The TumorMap supports the analysis of large-scale multi-omics comparisons and was developed as part of our data analysis center for the TCGA project. The project will create open source components and extend the viewing to single cell datasets.

The UCSC Cell Browser is a fast, light-weight atlas viewer for single cell data. It features a splittable t-SNE view, fast navigation, violin plots for genes, marker gene display, download of the current selection and custom annotations. Datasets can be arranged in a hierarchy as "collections". The main website at https://cells.ucsc.edu hosts more than a dozen well-annotated datasets added in collaboration with the original datasets authors, but the browser was designed to be easy to setup on any other webserver. As a result third party groups have started to integrate the browser into their own websites and tools. The popular packages Seurat and Scanpy include exporters into the Cell Browser format. We also provide importers for other data formats, like 10X Cellranger.

Cell-cell communication mediated by receptor-ligand complexes is crucial for coordinating diverse biological processes, such as development, differentiation and responses to infection. In order to understand how the context-dependent crosstalk of different cell types enables physiological processes to proceed, we developed CellPhoneDB, a novel repository of ligands, receptors and their interactions. Our repository takes into account the subunit architecture of both ligands and receptors, representing heteromeric complexes accurately. We integrated our resource with a statistical framework that predicts enriched cellular interactions between two cell types from single-cell transcriptomics data. CellPhoneDB v2.0 is a novel version of our resource that incorporates additional functionalities to allow users to introduce new interacting molecules and reduce the time and resources needed to interrogate large datasets. CellPhoneDB v2.0 is publicly available at https://github.com/Teichlab/cellphonedb and as a user-friendly web interface at http://www.cellphonedb.org/.

The Caenorhabditis Natural Diversity Resource (CaeNDR) is a collection of data and tools to study natural variation across Caenorhabditis briggsae, Caenorhabditis elegans, and Caenorhabditis tropicalis wild strains. We provide information about the environmental niche where each wild strain was isolated, all raw and processed whole-genome sequence and variant data, comparative genomics tools, and a genome-wide association (GWA) mapping portal. We propose to add three critical tools and web interfaces: phenotype tracking and analysis, CRISPR-Cas9 guide RNA selection and genotyping, and insertion-deletion variant genotyping. These three enhancements will make CaeNDR into one of the most powerful comparative genomics platforms in animals. CaeNDR is not one open-source software project but a collection of data (strain information, whole-genome sequence and variants, GWA mapping results), software projects (vcf-kit, cegwas2, comparative genomics tools), and interpretative tools (plots, user interfaces, markdown reports). This support will enable the expansion of data types (phenotypes) and molecular genetic tools (CRISPR-Cas9 genome editing and insertion-deletion variant genotyping). In the future, we will package the code, file structures, and web interfaces into a singular platform (Docker container running on Google Cloud Platform) that can be applied to any species with whole-genome sequence files from wild strains enabling future species-wide analyses.

ChrAccR is an R package that facilitates user-friendly analyses of large chromatin accessibility datasets comprising data quality control, exploratory analyses (including unsupervised methods for dimension reduction, clustering and quantifying transcription factor activities) and the identification and characterization of differentially accessible regions. It can be used for the analysis of large bulk datasets comprising hundreds of samples as well as for single-cell datasets with 10s to 100s of thousands of cells. Requiring only a limited set of R commands, ChrAccR generates analysis reports that can be interactively explored, facilitate a comprehensive analysis overview of the dataset and are easily shared with collaborators. The package is therefore particularly useful for users with limited bioinformatic expertise, researchers new to chromatin analysis or institutional core facilities providing ATAC-seq as a service. Additionally, the package provides numerous utility functions for custom R scripting that allow more in-depth analyses of chromatin accessibility datasets.

SCENIC (Single-CEll regulatory Network Inference and Clustering) enables biologists to infer transcription factors, gene regulatory networks and cell types from single-cell RNA-seq data. Available as R/Bioconductor package and Python package. Also available as workflow (Nextflow). Depends on "cisTarget databases", which are currently available at https://resources.aertslab.org/cistarget/.

For the analysis of single-cell ATAC-seq data, using probabilistic topic modeling, we have developed cisTopic, available at https://github.com/aertslab/cistopic.

The UCSC TumorMap is a Google Maps-like browser to investigate large-scale cancer genomics datasets. The TumorMap supports the analysis of large-scale multi-omics comparisons and was developed as part of our data analysis center for the TCGA project. The project will create open source components and extend the viewing to single cell datasets.

Clustergrammer2 is an interactive heatmap WebGL Jupyter Widget for visualizing high-dimensional data (e.g. a DataFrame). Clustergrammer2 was built to enable biologists and computational biologists to interactively explore single cell data (e.g. scRNA-seq data).

Despite the availability of web-based tools to process raw NGS data, all of them face the challenges of large data transfer, computing scalability, pipeline flexibility, and analysis reproducibility.  We began to develop CNAP (Cloud-Native Analysis Platform), which is hosted on GCP and designed to 1) provide user-friendly genomic data transfer mechanism; 2) utilize Workflow Description Language (WDL) and scientific workflow engine to manage analysis pipelines on cloud computing; 3) enforce analysis reproducibility; and 4) allow developers to create graphical user interfaces (GUIs) via a basic JSON-format file.  The goal is to provide a seamless and flexible process that will allow users to start their analysis with a series of raw genomic data preprocessed in automated fashion streamline the results to WebMeV.
rg_name: Cloud Native Analysis Platform (CNAP) and WebMeV

description:
Development of extensions to Open Data Kit X applications (ODK Survey, ODK Service, ODK Tables as well as enhanced tooling for data export) as well as development of a decision support system (also built on the ODK platform) and finally contribution to ODK X in the form of community forum activities, capacity building, as well as contributions to documentation and possibly bug reporting and fixing.

Extensions include various new question types to better support longitudinal studies in the context of health research as well as field use in remote rural areas.

The system to support decision making by community health workers (CHWs) will be developed on the ODK platform and made freely available on github.

The project is focused on enabling the broad usability of a software for simulating the dynamics of microbial communities. The software, called COMETS (Computation of Microbial Ecosystems in Time and Space), will enable users to implement simulations of complex spatial configurations of different microbial species and environments towards understanding the fundamental rules that govern microbial community metabolism and dynamics. Or goal is for this software, already used by a number of groups for simulating microbial ecosystem processes, to become a standard tool in the study of microbiomes. In addition to redesigning the graphic user interface for easier access, and to adding new modules for simulation of processes relevant to the gut microbiome, we will facilitate the growth of a community of developers. We expect that the collective contributions to this endeavor by groups with different expertise and goals in microbiome research will lead to a unique, broadly applicable tool which will integrate multiple microbial processes under a single in silico platform. Akin to a “weather prediction” computational engine, we envisage that COMETS could become a predictive microbiome forecast engine with multiple biomedical applications.

We present *AMARETTO as a software toolbox for network biology and medicine, towards developing a data-driven platform for diagnostic, prognostic and therapeutic decision-making in complex diseases. *AMARETTO links diseases, drivers, targets and drugs via network graph-based fusion of multi-omics, clinical, imaging, and driver and drug perturbation data across model systems and patient studies of complex diseases.

The *AMARETTO platform features a modular approach to incorporating prior biological knowledge based on multimodal and multiscale network-structured modeling: (1) AMARETTO learns networks of regulatory circuits - circuits of drivers and target genes - from functional genomics or multi-omics data and associates these circuits to clinical, molecular and imaging-derived phenotypes within each biological system (e.g., model systems or patients); (2) Community-AMARETTO learns subnetworks of regulatory circuits that are shared or distinct across networks derived from multiple biological systems (e.g., model systems and patients, cohorts and individuals, diseases and etiologies, in vitro and in vivo systems); (3) Perturbation-AMARETTO maps genetic and chemical perturbations in model systems onto patient-derived multi-omics networks for driver and drug discovery, respectively, and prioritizes lead drivers, targets and drugs for follow-up with experimental validation; (4) Imaging-AMARETTO maps radiographic and histopathology imaging data onto the patient-derived multi-omics networks for non-invasive and histopathology imaging diagnostics.

This software project contains the backend services code to support Data Use Oversight System User Interface. Data Use Oversight System is a semi-automated management service for compliant secondary use of data. There are typically restrictions associated with the use of controlled datasets to which researchers must agree. This software project delivers services for the creation, tracking, and approval of data researchers’ data access requests. Data Access Committees are associated with datasets hosted on the Precision Medicine platform and can vote on requests directly in Data Use Oversight System. Additionally, Data Use Oversight System leverages a matching algorithm that compares the researcher’s statement of intended use to the data use limitations from the provider to make a suggestion regarding access approval. The Data Access Committee members and chairperson make the final determination of access. Summary statistics and history of past votes are maintained in the system for auditing.
rg_name: Data Use Oversight System -- Web Services

description: This project started as a tool for curating gel images displaying protein co-purification banding patterns resulting from affinity capture followed by e.g. SDS-PAGE and protein staining. It has since been modified in a number of ways to increase functionality. The core functionality is storage of the experimental conditions and comparison of  the resulting protein banding patterns and mass spectrometry (or other proteomic) results obtained under different affinity capture conditions. Currently the database of curated genes and proteins is supported for S. cerevisiae, E. coli, mouse, and human. The project supports curation of protein identifications from common search engines, including X! Tandem, SEQUEST, Mascot and also accepts MSGFPlus file format. This site also includes data sharing features to foster collaborations and allows users to make their experimental data public at any time (or keep them private until publication). If funded, we will revamp this site as a hub for the new copurification framework, supporting access to the combined features of all the tools described below.

xiNET is a visualization tool for exploring cross-linking/mass spectrometry results. The interactive maps of the cross-link network that it generates are a type of node-link diagram. In these maps xiNET displays: (1) residue resolution positional information including linkage sites and linked peptides; (2) all types of cross-linking reaction product; (3) ambiguous results; and, (4) additional sequence information such as domains. xiNET runs in a browser and exports vector graphics which can be edited in common drawing packages to create publication quality figures.

The Complex-Traits Genetics Virtual Lab (CTG-VL) is an open source web platform that allows researchers to analyze data derived from genome-wide association studies (GWAS). CTG-VL compiles dozens of open-source analysis software and pipelines and hundreds of genomic datasets for researchers to interrogate their data. Briefly, CTG-VL can be used to identify genes and biological pathways involved in disease by mining data from GWAS. Moreover, as it contains hundreds of datasets that users have made publicly available, it can be used to identify similarities between diseases (e.g. shared genes and biological pathways), as well as assessing whether a trait or condition contribute to an increased risk of a disease. The backend of CTG-VL along with all the underlying datasets is hosted in the National eResearch Collaboration Tools and Resources (NECTAR) cloud and has been written in Node.js. The front-end is a single page application written in Angular 6 and allows users without bioinformatic expertise to carry out these analyses as well as interacting with datasets that would otherwise take months to download and integrate in their servers. We update CTG-VL approximately once a week with new datasets or analysis tools. Funding of this application will allow us to further its impact.

cwl-source is a repository for command line tools and workflows described by the Common Workflow Language (CWL). It describes and enforces best practices for CWL files and associated metadata which makes them more usable by a broad community. The repository directory structure allows for separation of complex tools with multiple subcommands into subtools which can inherit common metadata and components from parent directories. Each version of a tool or workflow is described separately and assigned a unique identifier to allow unambiguous referencing.  Input files which specify use cases of the tools and workflows are also assigned identifiers for referencing and have associated metadata to allow users to understand how tools and workflows are used. The metadata for each CWL file is required to describe the state of development of the file using a valid semantic version. The repository contains python scripts to initialize CWL and metadata files with the proper directory structure and validate content. The functions used in the scripts are used in a testing suite which is also the basis for continuous integration using Travis CI.

Data Analysis using Bootstrap-coupled ESTimation in Matlab (DABEST-Matlab) is a software package that enables the analysis of grouped data with estimation graphics. Such plots have the advantages of (1) placing the focus on effect-size quantification (2) offering a transparent, comprehensive visualization of both the observed values and the inferred effect-size distribution. The DABEST-Matlab package was the first to be written, as Matlab is widely used in neuroscience, the field of the authors. The code allows the user to visualize the observed values as scatterplots; it calculates the effect size and confidence intervals of the difference between multiple groups; and plots the results on the same figure. This figure design allows for a visual inspection of the observed values distribution, and displays the differences between multiple groups of data.

DataKnots is a Julia library for querying data with an extensible, practical and coherent algebra of query combinators.  DataKnots is designed to let data analysts and other accidental programmers query and analyze complex structured data.

DataKnots implements an algebraic query interface of Query Combinators. This algebra’s elements, or queries, represent relationships among class entities and data types. This algebra’s operations, or combinators, are applied to construct query expressions.

We seek to prove that this query algebra has significant advantages over the state of the art:

* DataKnots is a practical alternative to SQL with a declarative syntax; this makes it suitable for use by domain experts.

*DataKnots' data model handles nested and recursive structures (unlike DataFrames or SQL); this makes it suitable for working with CSV, JSON, XML, and SQL databases.

* DataKnots has a formal semantic model based upon monadic composition; this makes it easy to reason about the structure and interpretation of queries.

* DataKnots is a combinator algebra (like XPath but unlike LINQ or SQL); this makes it easier to assemble queries dynamically.

* DataKnots is fully extensible with Julia; this makes it possible to specialize it into various domain specific query languages.

We propose to develop a powerful toolkit consisting of a suite of structure learning algorithms that visualizes/interpretes high-dimensional static data, with an emphasis on single cell genomics datasets, in order to uncover the underlying structure of complex biological
progression.

Decode and encode neuronal signals in the brain.

The Neuralink's N1 chip produces output data in the form of spikes .

The goal of this software is to decode what the person is actually thinking from this spike data as input.

Focus will be on the primary motor cortex area which is responsible for speech , movement of arm and hand to restore speech on paralysed person.
rg_name: Software for encoding and decoding the active potentials of neurons in the brain

description:
DeepBehavior was a project to automate the analysis of animal and human behavior data.
Here in this proposal, we are focusing on the human 3D movement analysis section of the DeepBehavior project. We plan to make it more user-friendly and enable the ability to run it on the Cloud platform.
The proposed work is expected to disseminate this technology to a broader research community.

Quantifying behavior is crucial for many applications in neuroscience, ethology, genetics, medicine, and biology. Videography provides easy methods for the observation and recording of animal behavior in diverse settings, yet extracting particular aspects of a behavior for further analysis can be highly time consuming. 

Here we present an efficient method for 3D markerless pose estimation based on transfer learning with deep neural networks that achieves excellent results (i.e. you can match human labeling accuracy) with minimal training data (typically 50-200 frames). We demonstrate the versatility of this framework by tracking various body parts in multiple species across a broad collection of behaviors. The package is open source, fast, robust, and can be used to compute 3D pose estimates.

The Dendro platform is an "open-source Dropbox" with added description features. It is a data storage and description platform designed to help researchers and other users to describe their data files, built on Linked Open Data and ontologies. Users can use Dendro to publish data in the platform itself or to CKAN, Zenodo, DSpace or EUDAT's B2Share and others.

The purpose of this project is to develop a dynamic mobile content ICT platform (OSS) through which dynamic content can be published to support the prevention of Type I Diabetes in children from 5 to 15 years of age in the Colombian Caribbean. Allowing families and children affected by type I diabetes, adopt prevention techniques, control monitoring and reduce the impact of this pandemic. As well as providing unaffected children and their families with knowledge for the prevention and expansion of this condition.
rg_name: Mobile ICT platform (ICT mobile kit) for the prevention of Type I Diabetes

description:
Magnetic Resonance Imaging (MRI) provides a non-invasive view into brain biology underlying human cognition. Neuroimaging in Python (NIPY) is a community that encompasses researchers and developers who use Python in analysis of MRI data. It facilitates adoption of open-source software through the development of software tools, support of a diverse user/developer community and the development of documentation and instructional materials.

Diffusion Imaging in Python (DIPY) is one of the most well-established projects developed by the NIPY community. It focuses on diffusion MRI (dMRI), which measures properties of long-range connections between different brain region. This communication network ("connectome") is crucially important to brain function.

DIPY implements a large range of methods, including 30 models for inferences about diffusion within each voxel; deterministic and probabilistic tractographye methods for connecting measurements in neighboring voxels into models of connections between brain regions; and tools for statistical analysis of brain connections, for clustering connections and for recognition of known anatomical
structures. DIPY also implements tools that are useful beyond the analysis of MRI data: image denoising, linear and non-linear image registration and computational geometry. Finally, DIPY provides tools for visualization of MRI data and the results of dMRI data analysis.

As the number of scRNA-seq datasets increases, a major challenge will be the standardization of measurements from multiple different scRNA-seq experiments enabling integrative and comparative analyses. However, scRNA-seq data can be confounded by severe batch effects and technical artifact. In addition, scRNA-seq experiments generally capture multiple cell-types with only partial overlaps across experiments making comparison and integration particularly challenging. To overcome these problems, we develop a software tool, dmatch, which can both remove unwanted technical variation and assign the same cell(s) from one scRNA-seq dataset to their corresponding cell(s) in another dataset. By design, our approach can overcome compositional heterogeneity and partial overlap of cell types in scRNA-seq data. It has two important applications: it will allow (1) comparisons of scRNA-seq data across experiments (e.g. between cells from healthy and disease samples) and (2) mapping of genetic variants that affect gene expression quantitative trait loci (eQTLs) in a cell-type-specific manner using scRNA-seq. All the methods will be implemented in user-friendly software and disseminated to the scientific community. We foresee that our effort will greatly improve the utility of scRNA-seq in both clinical and basic research.
rg_name: Dmatch : a fast and accurate alignment tool of single-cell RNA-seq samples

description: Dockeye is an interactive virtual simulation tool to aid in drug discovery. The software is design to help biomedical researchers and the pharmaceutical industry overcome early bottlenecks in the drug discovery pipeline.

The dREG predicts the location of enhancers and promoters using PRO-seq, GRO-seq, or ChRO-seq data. We also developed an online cloud platform – the dREG Science Gateway which uses a pre-trained dREG models to identify transcript regulation elements  across the genome. The current dREG model works in any mammalian organism.
rg_name: The dREG Science Gateway for Interpreting Genome Sequences

We invented The WashU Epigenome Browser (http://epigenomegateway.wustl.edu/) in 2011. Over the past eight years, the browser has undergone rapid development both conceptually and in software and IT infrastructure, and it has built a large user base. We aim to develop general-purpose software with pioneering features. Past accomplishments include being the first to allow investigators to zoom and pan their view, rearrange tracks, and visualize and manipulate hundreds of genomic datasets. We have been the de facto gateway to data generated by the Roadmap Epigenomics Project. We also host data from other large consortia such as ENCODE, International Human Epigenome Consortium (IHEC), TCGA, Toxicant Exposures and Responses by Genomic and Epigenomic Regulators of Transcription (TaRGET) and 4DN. Our goal is to provide biologists with a broad range of interactivities enabled by modern web technology and the flexibility to interact with the data in any way they can imagine. The time is ripe for developing two essential functions we now propose in this application: exploring genomic data in a 3D genome and Virtual Reality. The new features will enable dynamic interaction with the 3D structure of the genome/chromatin, along with associated epigenomic data, and integrating chromatin imaging data.

EMAN2 is a broadly based greyscale scientific image processing suite with a primary focus on processing data from transmission electron microscopes. EMAN's original purpose was performing single particle reconstructions (3-D volumetric models from 2-D cryo-EM images) at the highest possible resolution, but the suite now also offers support for single particle cryo-ET, and tools useful in many other subdisciplines such as helical reconstruction, 2-D crystallography and whole-cell tomography. EMAN2 is capable of processing large data sets (>100,000 particle) very efficiently.

EMAN2 is one of the most well-established and widely used scientific image processing suites targeting the rapidly growing CryoEM/CryoET community worldwide. EMAN2 is a versatile, modular suite capable of performing a variety of image processing tasks with hundreds of algorithms supporting virtually all of the standard file formats and mathematical conventions used in the field, in addition to other related imaging fields. It provides an ideal platform for prototyping fundamental new algorithm developments, as well as also being able to achieve data-limited resolutions for single particle reconstructions and subtomogram averaging.

Enrichr is a web-based gene-set search engine application that includes the largest collection of gene-set libraries, alternative approaches to rank enriched terms, and various interactive visualizations to display enrichment results. Enrichr can be embedded in other tools that perform gene list analyses using its fast and well-documented API. Enrichr currently contains >300K annotated gene sets organized into >150 gene set libraries and it is currently serving ~700 users each day. Overall, Enrichr is a comprehensive and widely used resource for searching curated gene sets. It is a search engine that integrates biological knowledge for reuse and discovery.

The EVcouplings method uses co-variation analysis and maximum entropy algorithms to extract functionally constrained  interaction patterns and compute 3D molecular structures from multiple sequence alignments of genomically derived sequences. We aim to make this method, its diverse applications and algorithmic derivatives widely available to the biological research community. The EVcouplings.org web services (currently 500 active monthly users) and funded by NIH until 2016, are in urgent need of maintenance and development. We plan to complete the re-engineering of the entire framework, from backend pipeline to REST API and flexible user interface. We plan to add new visualization options and API links from and to widely used biological information resources, such as cBioPortal, Human Protein Atlas, and Human Cell Atlas. The most frequent user request would be “for my protein(s) of interest, show me the computed folds, complexes and inferred functional molecular interactions, with links to evidence”. The answers provided will valuable information support for cell biological research in both health and disease.
rg_name: Evolutionary couplings - tools and web services

description: Fluorescence calcium imaging is one of the preferred methods to record neuronal activity.  The algorithms necessary to extract biologically relevant information from fluorescent signals of calcium indicators (e.g., action potential firing in neurons) are complex and require significant expertise in programming to develop robust analysis pipelines. Unfortunately, despite the availability of affordable miniscopes and 2-photon microscopes, the publicly available methods for performing these analyses are custom-written, often poorly annotated and lack intuitive graphic user interfaces (GUI).  As a result, there exists a barrier for many laboratories to adopt these tools, especially for potential users without sufficient programming knowledge. Indeed, the bottleneck is no longer the hardware, but the software to analyze the calcium data. We propose to address this unmet need by creating an open-source, easy to use, GUI-based, intuitive and automated data analysis software (EZcalcium) for analyzing dynamic fluorescence calcium signals from defined regions of interest.

Tracking small animal behavior by video is one of the most common tasks in the fields of neuroscience and psychology. Although commercial software exists for the execution of this task, this software often presents enormous cost to the researcher, and can also entail purchasing specific hardware setups that are expensive and lack adaptability. Moreover, the inaccessibility of the code underlying this software renders them inflexible. Alternatively, available open source options frequently require extensive model training and can be challenging for those inexperienced with programming. Here we present an open source and platform independent set of behavior analysis pipelines using interactive Python (iPython/Jupyter Notebook) that researchers with no prior programming experience can use. Two modules are described. One module can be used for the positional analysis of an individual animal across a session (i.e., location tracking), amenable to a wide range of behavioral tasks including conditioned place preference, water maze, light-dark box, open field, and elevated plus maze, to name but a few. A second module is described for the analysis of conditioned freezing behavior. For both modules, a range of interactive plots and visualizations are available to confirm that chosen parameters produce results that conform to the user’s approval.

FAVITES (FrAmework for VIral Transmission and Evolution Simulation) is a robust modular framework for the simultaneous simulation of a transmission network and viral evolution, as well as simulation of sampling imperfections of the transmission network and of the sequencing process. The framework is robust in that the simulation process has been broken down into a series of interactions between abstract module classes, and the user can simply plug in each desired module implementation (or implement one from scratch) to customize any stage of the simulation process.

Currently, we generate more multi-omics data than we have the resources to analyse; existing bioinformatics approaches cannot keep up. Furthermore, computational irreproducibility is still plaguing the biomedical field. Workflow managers and containers have helped make bioinformatics analysis workflows more portable, reproducible and scalable. Yet, major challenges still persist. Current workflows are monolithic in nature, making it difficult for scientists to create, update and reproduce them. Simultaneously, the fast evolution of bioinformatics software, requires researchers to continuously create and update workflows. And lastly, building and running monolithic analysis workflows is very time-consuming and requires substantial computational skills, which few researchers possess. FlowCraft introduces a paradigm shift from a monolithic to a microcomponent workflow development architecture, overcoming the major challenges in the field of bioinformatics. In this new paradigm, users solely focus on developing microcomponents, while FlowCraft takes care of ‘stitching’ them into functional workflows according to the ‘recipes’ specified by the user. This democratises, simplifies and fast-tracks the process of building, updating and reproducing workflows, while also facilitating communication among collaborators, as users only need to provide a ‘recipe’ rather than long complex documentation.
rg_name: FlowCraft: a component-based workflow composer for omics analysis using Nextflow.

description: Fluocell is a software package for the analysis and visualization of fluorescence images of live cells, with applications in migration and cancer invasion. The main package contains a visualization and quantification tool for fluorescence intensity and FRET ratio images. Optional modules of diffusion analysis and polarity analysis can be obtained upon request. This package is mainly written in MATLAB. It is being developed by a group of researchers in the "Molecular Engineering for Single Cell Imaging and Reprogramming" at University of California, San Diego. As developers, we are open for collaboration on using the software or developing additional features. If you find this software package of interest or useful for your work, please take the time to cite our work and write an email to tell us, since positive feedbacks are important to secure continuous support for this software.

Fitting Oscillations and One-Over-F (FOOOF) is a fast, efficient, physiologically-informed model to parameterize neural power spectra, characterizing both the aperiodic “background” component, and periodic components as overlying peaks, reflecting putative oscillations.

The model conceives of the neural power spectrum as consisting of two distinct functional processes: 1) an aperiodic component, typically reflecting 1/f-like characteristics, modeled with an exponential fit, with: 2) band-limited peaks rising above this background, reflecting putative oscillations, and modeled as Gaussians.

With regards to examining peaks in the frequency domain, as putative oscillations, the benefit of the FOOOF approach is that these peaks are characterized in terms of their specific center frequency, amplitude and bandwidth without requiring predefining specific bands of interest. In particular, it separates these peaks from a dynamic, and independently interesting aperiodic signal. This conception of the aperiodic signal as potentially functional (and therefore worth carefully modeling) is based on work from the Voytek lab and others that collectively shows that the aperiodic signal changes across task demands and participant demographics, and that it may index underlying excitation/inhibition (EI) balance.

freebayes is a Bayesian genetic variant detector designed to find small polymorphisms, specifically SNPs (single-nucleotide polymorphisms), indels (insertions and deletions), MNPs (multi-nucleotide polymorphisms), and complex events (composite insertion and substitution events) smaller than the length of a short-read sequencing alignment.

freebayes is haplotype-based, in the sense that it calls variants based on the literal sequences of reads aligned to a particular target, not their precise alignment. This model is a straightforward generalization of previous ones (e.g. PolyBayes, samtools, GATK) which detect or report variants based on alignments. This method avoids one of the core problems with alignment-based variant detection--- that identical sequences may have multiple possible alignments.

freebayes uses short-read alignments (BAM files with Phred+33 encoded quality scores, now standard) for any number of individuals from a population and a reference genome (in FASTA format) to determine the most-likely combination of genotypes for the population at each position in the reference. It reports positions which it finds putatively polymorphic in variant call file (VCF) format. It can also use an input set of variants (VCF) as a source of prior information, and a copy number variant map (BED) to define non-uniform ploidy variation across the samples under analysis.

We have made a concerted effort to make FreeSurfer available outside of our lab by open sourcing the code,  packaging the program for easy download and install, creating massive amounts of documentation, holding classes, supporting users through an email forum, and attempting to hide the complexity of the underlying operations so that those without the technical sophistication can still use the programs. In our opinion, we have been wildly successful (see Table 1) . But it has not been easy. FreeSurfer currently consists of about 800,000 lines of C/C++ code plus many shell and python scripts. FreeSurfer has been developed over the last 20 years by academics (professors, post docs, graduate students). The main goals of these people were academic, i.e., to produce results for manuscripts, grants, and collaborations; rigorous programming techniques, documentation, and ease-of-use came second. These efforts were funded by grants from the US government through the National Institutes of Health (NIH). NIH is primarily interested in hypothesis driven research, not software development, documentation, and testing. As a result, it has been difficult to apply modern programming standards to FreeSurfer. If funded, this proposal would help modernize FreeSurfer.

Celligrate is a project to develop an essential software package for downstream cell type characterization and integration of scRNA-seq datasets. Celligrate includes two customized learning methods: the NS-Forest  (a machine learning-based method for cell type-specific marker gene selection) and FR-Match (a statistical learning method for cluster-to-cluster cell type matching) packages developed by our group, which can be applied to scRNA-seq gene expression matrices with cell cluster membership information. The use of Celligrate extends the utility of the upstream scRNA-seq analysis pipelines to downstream use cases, and ultimately accelerates the growth of knowledge about cell types by integrating results from individual studies.  In this Essential Open Source Software (EOSS) project, we will build a self-contained extensible software infrastructure for cell type matching using NS-Forest/FR-Match and two other established matching methods - scmap for cell-to-cluster mapping and Seurat-CCA for cell-to-cell alignment - to close the gap between individual study scRNA-seq analyses and integrated cell type knowledge extraction. The proposed infrastructure will include independently-implemented analytical software modules, API interface with primary data sources, and compatibility with different programming languages, including Python/SCANPY and R/Bioconductor.
rg_name: Celligrate: essential software for robust single cell RNA-seq cell type integration

description: Lack of computationally reproducible and interoperable software for bacterial variant analysis has forced researchers to use the human optimized GATK software due to its high sensitivity for low and variable allele fraction variants. However, the GATK has not been tested or optimized for non-human use cases. The GATK already has several tweaks to local assembly that improves sensitivity to low-allele fraction variants even in the case of highly-varying depths, which is a typical challenge in bacterial variant analysis. Detecting SNVs and indels at variable read depths is crucial for studying bacterial genetic heterogeneity, evolution, epidemiology, transmission, and antibiotic resistance mechanisms. With this pilot project we would like to further identify the key areas in which we can develop the GATK software to be more sensitive to real variants and filter artifacts in bacterial genomics data.
rg_name: GATK Methods for Bacterial Variant Discovery and Evaluation

description: This nascent website will house curated metadata, feature predictions for phenotypes (transcripts), a json index of haploblocks and variants, eQTLs, and breeding hypotheses.  It will also guide users in how to download and use versioned software used to generate these datasets, in addition to housing said software.
Initial implementation of analysis workflow (in Nextflow) performing gene-level metagenomic analysis from WGS data in FASTQ format.

GENIE is the name of the MPEG-G (and ISO) compliant encoder-decoder pair we are developing. It can represent both raw (FASTQ files) and aligned (SAM/BAM/CRAM files) genomic data. In addition to supporting several compression modes, the compressed data is encapsulated in a manner that allows for efficient operations on localized regions over the compressed data. In addition, GENIE contains the underlying technology of the algorithms that govern the compressors of FASTQ and SAM files developed by part of the members of the proposed team. The current implementation has been developed by several institutions and members that are active participants of the MPEG-G initiative. The goal of this proposal is to convert the current implementation into an industry-grade solution, which will include efficient parallelization, extensive testing, detailed documentation, and an intuitive interface, among others. In addition, we will extend and improve the functionalities supported by the current implementation to include optional encryption of part of the data, annotations related to regions of the genome, and packetization of the compressed data for efficient streaming, among others.

GenomeSeer is a collection of genomics analysis workflows that are used for detecting single nucleotide variants (SNVs), insertions/deletions (indels), copy number variants (CNVs) and translocations from RNA and DNA sequencing.  These workflows have been validated in a CLIA laboratory at UTSW

Genomic Interactive Visualization Engine (GIVE) is a customizable modular genome browser engine that can be embedded in any web pages with ease. Users can embed a fully functional genome browser with multiple side-by-side views with only several lines of HTML code in their pages.

Visualize sequences in (modified) logo plots. The design choices used by these logo plots allow sequencing data to be more easily analyzed. Because it is integrated into the 'ggplot2' geom framework, these logo plots support native features such as faceting.
We propose to develop Giotto, a comprehensive, flexible, robust, and open-source pipeline for spatial data analysis and visualization.
rg_name: Giotto, Spatial Data Analysis and Visualization

description:
GiraffeTools: Tools for a Graphical Interface for Reproducible Analysis For workFlow Experiments

GiraffeTools provides an interactive workflow editor in which you can visually build a pipeline such that your analysis code is automatically generated. You can save the graphical workflow as well as its code representation to GitHub. Someone else can inspect your visual workflow and only needs to fork your repository if they want to continue where you left off. 

Currently, GiraffeTools supports data analysis for MRI data and automatically produces Python code. Extensions are currently made to support Keras/TensorFlow. The extensibility of GiraffeTools allows for user-added content within existing toolboxes, as well as user-added toolboxes in general. We will add major contributions centrally, but these extensions can also be added and configured on the client side.

GiraffeTools projects are GitHub repositories and thereby inherit the version control and branching functionality and the privacy settings. GiraffeTools offers a project page for every repository from which which the user can inspect the visual workflow at any branch or previous commit.

Grafoscopio is a moldable tool tomake reproducible research and literate computing, developedon Pharo live coding and computing integrated environment, which allow authors to intertwine prose, code, data and agile visualizations into storytelling, and readers and coauthors can verify, collaborate on and extend the document claims and artifacts.

Grafoscopio is and integrates simple and self-contained “pocket infrastructures”, that canbe execute On/Off-line, from a USB thumb drive, a raspberry-Pi like computer, a modestserver or any hardware in between and beyond and tries to blur binary constructs like author / reader, developer / user, document / data, binary application / source code, andhas an associated permanent workshop+hackathon, called the Data Week, where diverse participants learn, extend and modify Grafoscopio, while dealing with civic issues that canbe understood and expressed better using the techniques provided by literate computing and reproducible research.

Graphmap is a highly sensitive tool for mapping DNA reads to the reference genome and pairwise read overlapping. Mapping is preferable way of assembling genomes when a genome for a particular species has already been determined. Graphmap2 is a recently published extension tailored for RNA mapping. RNA mapping is challenging for eukaryotic genomes where genes usually consist of coding regions (exons), interrupted by noncoding regions (introns). After transcription of the whole gene to pre-mRNA, in a process called splicing, introns are removed and exons joined to form a contiguous coding sequence. Once we have an RNA read we need to find the positions of all exons this read contains taking care about unknown introns. 
The alignments produced by Graphmap/Graphmap2 are highly precise. Many RNA reads are correctly mapped with the precision of mapping edges of exons up to a single nucleotide base.  
Graphmap is written in C++ for Linux and macOS
.
We plan to (i) increase performances with novel mapping engine tailored for the last generation of high quality long reads, (ii) reorganize the  code (iii) add output of novel genes and transcripts to Graphmap2 (iii) add detailed description of all options and usage examples.

GROBID is an Open Source tool for parsing and extracting structured information from technical and scientific documents in raw format like PDF. The large majority of the scholar documents is only available in PDF, a format not adapted to text mining and corpus analysis. Even when a publisher XML format is available, the level of structuring might not be sufficient and uniform, so further processing and harmonization are often necessary.

GROBID has been developed to address these issues in a reliable, fast and scalable manner thanks to machine learning techniques (cascaded sequence labelling models, CRF and RNN). We see this tool as the first building block of a text mining infrastructure.
