GROBID delivers state-of-the-art accuracy, with a particular focus on speed, scalability and production. Deployments in production includes ResearchGate, HAL Research Archive, EPO, INIST-CNRS, Mendeley, CERN, Internet Archive, Elsevier, etc. 

GROBID is distributed under Apache 2.0 license.

GNU Guix is a package management tool for the reproducible deployment of software, independent of the host operating system.  Guix offers a declarative, stateless approach to environment management and makes it easy for unprivileged users to install, upgrade, or remove software packages, to roll back to a previous package set, to build packages from source, and generally assists with the creation and maintenance of bit-reproducible software environments.
It can reproducibly generate application bundles in various container formats and enables the seamless use of applications across different GNU/Linux system distributions.
Guix comes with a large collection of scientific software, including hundreds of tools from the bioinformatics and machine learning domains.

Hail is a scalable genetics platform that seeks to address one of the defining problems in life sciences: the exponential growth of sequencing data has finally, and significantly, outpaced the abilities of individual computers to process it. In short order, datasets will readily consist of millions of samples. The era of distributed computing is upon us, and Hail is the first, and to our knowledge only major effort, to provide a transparent distributed programming language for genetics that addresses this challenge of scale.

Hail's core advantages are the terseness of its syntax and its ability to distribute fault-tolerant workloads to tens of thousands of CPU cores. In our experience analyzing some of the largest datasets to date, including UK Biobank (500,000 samples) and gnomAD (141,456 samples), we've found Hail to reduce the length of genomics scripts by an order of magnitude, while also improving the performance of those programs by 3-4 orders of magnitude.

The goal of this project is to implement homomorphic encryption (HE) technology that allows approximate fixed point arithmetics on encrypted data without decryption. This software package supports basic cryptography algorithms (e.g., parameters setup, generation of keys, encryption, and decryption) as well as advanced functions (e.g, ciphertext addition, multiplication, rotation). We provide a simple and convenient API with the state of the art performance. In practice, it has shown remarkable performance in real world applications that require arithmetic over real numbers (where small numeric errors in the least significant bits will not change results, e.g., machine learning, statistical testing, control systems). We adapted the approximate HE scheme to present the best solution to 2017 iDASH (integrating Data for Analysis, Anonymization, Sharing) Genome Privacy and Security Competition to train a logistic regression model training on encrypted data.

Working in conjunction with the StandardHealthRecord.org and SyntheticMass.org projects (funded by the MITRE corporation), we will utilize all human data elements mapped to the social determinants of health (clinical, biological and genetic, societal, environmental, cultural). This data-driven summary of the Determinants of Health (DoH) will aid health decision making at the individual level through high-level composite views of an individuals health and well-being. We will envision the service by designing views that use this composite health score.

This project will set the stage for ensuring that every person in the future has a standard health record that they own and interrogate. This will set the stage for healthcare services and products to have a precision medicine lens, in which personal data drives health decisions and evolves services. A future in which simple, non-invasive personal diagnostics are the norm, and where seamless machine- and clinician-driven services work for patients and their families.

The UCSC TumorMap is a Google Maps-like browser to investigate large-scale cancer genomics datasets. The TumorMap supports the analysis of large-scale multi-omics comparisons and was developed as part of our data analysis center for the TCGA project. The project will create open source components and extend the viewing to single cell datasets.

The UCSC TumorMap is a Google Maps-like browser to investigate large-scale cancer genomics datasets. The TumorMap supports the analysis of large-scale multi-omics comparisons and was developed as part of our data analysis center for the TCGA project. The project will create open source components and extend the viewing to single cell datasets.

One disease can be caused by different genetic variations of several genes belonging to the same signaling pathway or a closely interacting network. There is no tool available to reveal the association between genetic heterogeneity and phenotype homogeneity, for a cohort of patients with the same disease. We therefore propose a cohort-oriented and network-based tool, Human Gene Connectome 2 (HGC2), to identify functionally close gene clusters harboring deleterious variants that have a causal relationship with a certain disease. HGC2 takes WES/WGS data from a cohort as input, filters the variants using certain criteria, tests gene-level significance against 2,500 healthy controls from 1,000 Genomes Project, and projects the candidate genes onto a global reference gene network. It will iteratively scan through all candidate genes for all patients in the cohort, to identify the gene clusters covering as many candidate genes as possible for as many patients as possible. The gene clusters will be enriched by KEGG/REACTOME pathways and gene ontologies. The cohort-specific and functionally enriched gene clusters will be the final output. We will present HGC2 as an open source software and webserver, to engage the computational community for further improvements, and to be user-friendly to biologists without computational experience.

HiC-Pro is an optimized and flexible pipeline for Hi-C data processing. It was designed to process Hi-C data, from raw fastq files (paired-end Illumina data) to normalized contact maps, including reads alignments, filtering, generation and normalization of contact maps, as well as quality controls and final reporting for the end users. 
It supports the main Hi-C protocols, including digestion protocols as well as protocols that do not require restriction enzymes such as DNase Hi-C. In practice, HiC-Pro was successfully applied to many data-sets including dilution Hi-C, in situ Hi-C, DNase Hi-C, Micro-C, capture-C, capture Hi-C or HiChip data.
The pipeline is flexible, scalable and optimized. It can operate either on a single laptop or on a computational cluster. HiC-Pro is sequential and each step of the workflow can be run independently. HiC-Pro includes a fast implementation of the iterative correction method for data normalization (iced python package) as well as additional functions for allele-specific analysis.

HiGlass is an open source visualization tool built on web technologies that provides a rich interface for rapid, multiplex, and multiscale navigation of 2D genomic maps alongside 1D genomic tracks, allowing users to combine various data types, synchronize multiple visualization modalities, and share fully customizable views with others. It was designed to support exploring different experimental conditions, comparing the results of analyses, and creating interactive snapshots to share with collaborators and the broader public. HiGlass is accessible online at http://higlass.io and is also available as a containerized application that can be run on any platform.

rg_name: hMRI: An open-source toolbox for quantitative MRI and in vivo histology using MRI

description: A Java API for high-throughput biological sequence data (HTS) file formats. HTSJDK provides a unified Java implementation for reading and writing common file formats, such as BAM, SAM and VCF, used for high-throughput sequencing data. There are also a number of useful utilities for manipulating HTS data.
Specifications of SAM/BAM and related high-throughput sequencing file formats.

We propose to develop Icy3.0, which will be the converging result of bringing together: 1. the advanced and generalizable data structure and image analysis library of ImgLib2 able to handle any size and type of images; 2. the standard-abiding framework of Icy bringing under a unique platform most of the common APIs and languages and easy access to HPC; 3. a totally new framework for integrating natively and in a seamless manner the major existing open-source AI libraries, and bring the ease of use of Icy to the training of neural networks.

iEDGE aims to find and prioritize genes and pathways likely to contribute to tumorigenesis through the analysis of cancer multi-omics datasets (e.g., TCGA). It implements an unbiased, genome-wide search whereby genetic and epigenetic variation is “propagated” forward and tested for association with gene expression variation. iEDGE first tests for the association between each (epi)DNA alteration event status (present/absent) and the gene expression of the genes falling within the alteration (Cis-Analysis); it then searches genome-wide for genes whose expression is associated with each alteration status (Trans-Analysis). Next, the significant cis-genes are tested for their ability to mediate the association between alterations and trans genes. Finally, cis- and trans-genes for each alteration are annotated by pathway enrichment analysis. Application of the method to the analysis of real cancer multi-omics data showed its effectiveness. Notably, cis gene drivers identified by iEDGE were found to be significantly enriched for known driver genes from multiple compendia of validated oncogenes and tumor suppressors. Furthermore, predicted drivers were enriched for functionally relevant cancer genes with amplification-driven dependencies, which are of potential prognostic and therapeutic value. These results are the main motivation behind our proposed effort to make the underlying tool broadly available to the research community.

ImagingAnalysis is a Mathematica package that performs a grid-based analysis of time-lapse images. The package creates time series from individual cell-sized grids and extracts unwrapped phases that can be directly adapted to Kuramoto-type modeling. It also estimates periods based on three independent measures: Fast Fourier Transform, slopes of the unwrapped phase, and peak-to-peak intervals. It detects peak positions and plots them as raster plots and histograms. It also plots the spatial distribution of oscillatory parameters, e.g. period. The package detrends the time series using the Hodrick-Prescott filter and normalizes the detrended time series by dimensional embedding or envelope curve estimation. It finds clusters using spectral clustering and partial correlations. It calculates the time-dependent phase coherence by Kuramoto Synchronization Index. It produces animations for the phase development in a clock-like format.

In 2015, we published an R package tcR—one of the first libraries designed to apply statistics and visualisations to AIRR data which quickly gained popularity with more than 20,000 users. Initially the tcR package was applicable only to TCR repertoires. The immunarch (immunoinformatics architecture) package was therefore conceived to supersede tcR in order to become a community standard. It not only has improved analysis and visualisation methods, but also it now contains means of analysis of both TCR and BCR repertoires. We aim to develop the package using modern product management approaches. Our goal is to improve and secure data analysis standards in the field, solve critical problems, and support researchers and communities. We believe that immunarch can accelerate immunogenomics studies helping scientists focus more on research and less on coding. It will make the cutting-edge methods accessible to biologists with little to no coding experience.

Humans vary considerably both in their baseline and activated cellular gene expression. To better understand this heterogeneity, many research groups are assaying different cell types and cohorts, generating unprecedented volumes of data. One such domain is the immune system. We have recently developed an open-source web-based tool, ImmuneRegulation, that enables users to interactively explore immune regulatory elements that drive cell-type, cohort- or stimuli specific gene expression. While we designed and developed ImmuneRegulation in human immune research domain, tremendous amounts of similar data exist in other domains (e.g. neuroscience, cardiovascular) and organisms (e.g. mice), and similar interactive analysis tools are urgently needed. Here, we aim to facilitate the adoption of ImmuneRegulation functionalities by multiple developer and user communities by packaging its code into modular Regulatory Elements VISual Exploration (REVISE) libraries and automating its code generation into autoREVISE tool. Software generated through this proposal will significantly lower the barriers between complex cellular regulation data and researchers who want rapid, intuitive and high-quality access to the effects of regulatory elements on gene expression in multiple domains, and empower investigators in translating these rich data into biological insights and clinical applications.
rg_name: Regulatory Elements VISual Exploration (REVISE) tool: multi-domain adoption

description: The inferelator is a code to learn networks and gene-gene interactions from genomics data.  The code is written in python (but until 3 years ago was an R package). We plan to support only the python package going forward. The code provides 1) preprocessing and data-integration steps (prior generation), 2) latent TF and rate estimation, 3) network inference and modeling, and 4) visualization and visualization interface support. The code models networks as sets of coupled differential equations when sufficient time series (or trajectory) information is present. The work presents a very flexible mathematical framework for data-integration and thus can be applied to many potential genomics experimental designs, thus necessitating that the code be accompanied by many worked examples, which we will implement in Jupyter. The code encompasses: 1) the preprocessing code, 2) the main code body for network inference, and 3) interfaces to visualization and worked example Jupyter notebooks.
Integrated Genome Browser is a fast, flexible, and free open source, desktop genome visualization tool implemented in Java.

Recent advances in next-generation sequencing generate a large amount of genomic data. While this facilitates evolutionary biologists to resolve many deep phylogenetic questions in the Tree of Life, large datasets pose major computational challenges for most software. 

Therefore, we have developed the open-source software IQ-TREE to tackle this challenge. We aim to improve speed and at the same time also maintain accuracy and flexibility. Since the first publication in 2013, IQ-TREE has been actively maintained by an international team and become widely-used in the scientific community.

“Isodyn” is a C++ program that performs an analysis of stable isotope tracer data to assess metabolic flux profiles in living cells. Isodyn simulates the dynamics of isotopic isomer (isotopomer) distribution in central metabolic pathways which reflect the characteristics of corresponding biochemical reactions and fits the simulated dynamics of mass isotopomers to those observed experimentally. The simulated metabolic fluxes that correspond to the best fit are assumed to reproduce the real fluxes in the analyzed biological object and conditions. Isodyn contains tools that check the goodness of fit and perform a statistical analysis of obtained metabolic fluxes.

Juicer is a one-click pipeline for Hi-C data processing and analysis. Juicer allows users without any computing experience to run a single command and obtain multiple resolution contact maps that are annotated and can be easily visualized. The contact maps are stored in a highly compressed indexed file format called .hic, which is designed to enable quick random access.

Sequencing data from a single Hi-C experiment can easily consume many terabytes. In order to handle such massive datasets, Juicer supports the use of high performance computing, parallelization, and hardware acceleration whenever possible, including CPU clusters, general-purpose graphics processing units (GPGPUs), and field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs). Juicer is also compatible with a variety of cloud and cluster architectures. 

Because Juicer is available on so many different architectures, researchers around the world have been able to use it to rapidly process their own data without needing to develop their own specialized software. Contributors in the community have added their own cluster architectures to the collection available. Juicer and the hic file format have been adopted as the standard for the field by the NIH consortia 4DN and ENCODE.

JupyterHub brings the power of notebooks to groups of users. It gives users access to computational environments and resources without burdening the users with installation and maintenance tasks. Users - including students, researchers, and data scientists - can get their work done in their own workspaces on shared resources which can be managed efficiently by system administrators.

JupyterHub runs on any shared computational resources, from single servers to the cloud to HPC centers, making it possible to serve a pre-configured data science environment to any user in the world. JupyterHub is customizable and scalable, and is suitable for small and large teams, academic courses, and large-scale infrastructure.

SoS Notebook is a Jupyter kernel, with frontend extensions to both classic Jupyter and JupyterLab, designed for interactive multi-language data analysis. The SoS kernel serves as the master kernel for all other Jupyter kernels and enables the use of multiple kernels in one notebook. With assistance from multiple language modules (sos-bash, sos-r, sos-matlab, etc), SoS Notebook allows data exchange among live kernels of supported languages.

The frontend extension to classic Jupyter adds a console panel for the execution of scratch commands and display of intermediate results and progress information, and a number of shortcuts and magics to enhance interactive data analysis. Working closely with the JupyterLab team, these features have been ported to JupyterLab, either in the sos extension or as core features of JupyterLab. 

SoS Notebook also serves as the IDE for the SoS Workflow that allows the development and execution of workflows from Jupyter notebooks. This not only enables easy transition of scripts developed for interaction data analysis to workflows running in containers and remote systems, but also the creation of scientific workflows in a format with narratives, sample input and output.

kallisto is a program for quantifying abundances of transcripts from bulk and single-cell RNA-Seq data, or more generally of target sequences using high-throughput sequencing reads. It is based on the novel idea of pseudoalignment for rapidly determining the compatibility of reads with targets, without the need for alignment. On benchmarks with standard RNA-Seq data, kallisto can quantify 30 million human reads in less than 3 minutes on a desktop computer using only the read sequences and a transcriptome index that itself takes less than 10 minutes to build. Pseudoalignment of reads preserves the key information needed for quantification, and kallisto is therefore not only fast, but also as accurate as existing quantification tools. In fact, because the pseudoalignment procedure is robust to errors in the reads, in many benchmarks kallisto significantly outperforms existing tools.

KymoButler is a deep learning-based open source software package designed to track objects using the so called kymogram approach. A kymogram is the combination of spatial and temporal data, often used to visualise a dynamic process in single image. The current version of KymoButler takes 2D kymograms (1D+time) and extracts object dynamics for a large variety of different processes, such as neuronal transport processes or cytoskeletal dynamics. To overcome the traditionally steep learning curve in adopting new software, we made KymoButler available in 3 forms: i) as a easy to use, drag and drop web-application, ii) as a cloud API that can be called in any programming language, and iii) as an open source Wolfram Language package to run on a local machine.
(see project summary on page 6)

This software implements the hardware drivers and image analysis software for the Lifespan Machine.  This software allows tens of thousands of nematodes to be imaged simultaneously during month-long continuous imaging runs. This software is in use in many labs worldwide including an NIH consortium project, the Caenorhabditis testing program (CITP).

The Linear Modelling toolbox is an application that offers a combination of advanced statistical methods specifically designed for Magneto- and Electro- Encephalographic data (i.e. the recording of ionic flow changes due to neural activity). The goal of the project is to provide modern and robust methods to perform statistical analyses from data which have typically been prepared within other end-user platforms. Compared to other packages, the LIMO toolbox not only uses a General Linear Model  approach but combines it with robust estimators (parameters resistant to outlier data) and does not assume particular distributions for the input data by using modern computer based resampling techniques for inference.

LORIS is an open source data management system that integrates all aspects of a scientific study, from data acquisition (imaging, clinical, behavioural, genetics), to storage, validation, processing, and dissemination. It provides an extensible framework that facilitates the development of a wide range of tools to support research studies. LORIS provides both an API to integrate data into pipelines, and a variety of user-friendly web-based modules.

Examples of modules written on the platform which support the open science movement are the:
1. Data Query Tool: lets users query arbitrary data from a web-based front end.
2. Publication module: lets users propose publications based on data collected in a LORIS instance.
3. Imaging module: enables user viewing and validation of medical images in real time from their web browser.
4. Quality Control module: facilitates scientists validating data entered into LORIS.
5. Genomic module: incorporates summary genetic data for cross-modal correlation analysis.

In total, LORIS comes with approximately 40 modules out of the box, and provides an architecture for studies to extend the platform in novel ways that support their research. It has been used in a variety of domains including single and multi-site imaging studies, epigenetic studies, biobanking, and institutional data hosting.

Nowadays, supporting human diagnosis in medical fields with computer based automatic systems is a reality. Such systems can find anomalies in patients’ charts synthesizing all kinds of readings, tuberculosis in chest X-rays, lesions in MRI images, etc. The results achieved in medical image analysis among others are tremendous. The supremacy of machine learning with deep neural networks and  automatic feature extraction is uncontestable in these achievements.  However, there is still a major impediment from medical personnel to adopt these methods. Due to the abstract nature of these machine-learning models, for medical doctors, these models act as black boxes that provide an answer for a given input without explaining the answer. The discovery process is hidden from the user and the extracted features lose the rich semantics of the original biomedical features so valuable to biomedical specialists. Therefore, we propose a software toolkit that supports preserving semantics instead of transforming the original input to something, which might make sense only to a machine. It is based on discovering and analyzing the dependencies of these characteristics using General Line Coordinates (GLC). GLC is a solid and already proven lossless mathematical representation of all kind of numerical input data with strong visualization capabilities
rg_name: Visual Knowledge Discovery and Machine Learning Tools for Biomedical Field

description: With the improvement of sequencing techniques, chromatin immunoprecipitation followed by high throughput sequencing (ChIP-Seq) is getting popular to study genome-wide protein-DNA interactions. To address the lack of powerful ChIP-Seq analysis method, we present a novel algorithm, named Model-based Analysis of ChIP-Seq (MACS), for identifying transcript factor binding sites. MACS captures the influence of genome complexity to evaluate the significance of enriched ChIP regions, and MACS improves the spatial resolution of binding sites through combining the information of both sequencing tag position and orientation. MACS can be easily used for ChIP-Seq data alone, or with control sample with the increase of specificity.

Our mission is to allow people to interpret sequencing results by removing barriers such as access to proprietary pipelines. We created a web-tool, available on http://marrvel.org/, that is freely available and accessible to anyone with a web-browser and an internet connection. MARRVEL is a one-stop data collection tool for human genes and variants and their orthologous genes in key genetic model organisms. In this proposal, we outline our plans to better address our goal of making sequence analysis accessible as well as add frequently requested features.
rg_name: MARRVEL(Model organism Aggregated Resources for Rare Variant ExpLoration)

description: The Cleveland Clinic's Center for Clinical Artificial Intelligence - Open Source AI Portal is a collaborative effort among CCF physician scientists to facilitate the familiarity and adoption of artificial intelligence among the world’s medical practitioners. The portal serves as a beginner friendly yet powerful research tool in which researchers can upload simple spreadsheets of deidentified patient data and watch in real time as all major machine learning and deep learning algorithms actively train and fit the data to a model. Each modeling algorithm is accompanied by an introduction and description of common characteristics. After computation, each model is scored for quality of fit and the various algorithms assessed are provided to the user in a rank ordered list, identifying which model best represents the provided data. The features driving each model (which correspond to the clinical factors provided in the data) are graphically represented to ensure interpretability and clinical relevance. Each model also has additional fine-tuning parameters that can later be explored and adjusted as the user becomes more familiar with training and testing data. The CCF AI Portal will be open source, hosted on flexible cloud computing resources, and free to use for research purposes without restriction.
rg_name: Cleveland Clinic's Center for Clinical Artificial Intelligence - Open Source AI Portal

description:
Structural information in relevant biological context is essential for the design of drugs as well as drug delivery systems and personalized medicine. One of the challenges of structural biology, structural biophysics and material science is to determine the high-resolution structure of large self-assembled complexes (that cannot be crystallized), made of many subunits (like lipids and proteins), in their native solution conditions. This information can then be used to unravel the underlying physics that dictates the formation mechanisms of complex structures from their subunits. 
 With the advent of modern synchrotron facilities, the resolution and sensitivity of solution scattering have been greatly improved over the past years. The challenge in solution X-ray scattering, however, is data analysis. To address this challenge, we would like to continue the development of  our powerful software called D+. D+ is based on docking atomic and/or geometric models into their assembly symmetry and do it in a hierarchical manner, in a bottom up approach, adding as many subunits as needed. The assembly symmetry defines the rotations and translations of repeating subunits in a large assembly. In this way, the solution scattering curve from any supramolecular structure can be modeled at any spatial resolution (including atomic).

DeepARG was developed in early 2018 that deploys deep learning to predict antibiotic resistance genes (ARGs) in big genomic and metagenomic sequencing data. Owning to its superior performance over existing methods, deepARG has quickly gained tremendous popularity to become state-of-the-art method for ARG prediction, and is now being used all over the world by scientists ranging from environmental engineers, geoscientists, to medical researchers. However, continued development and maintenance has been very challenging if not impossible. Recently with the departure of the original creator Gustavo Arango, we are now faced with insufficient time and labor for extending the capability of deepARG and updating the deepARG models with the latest research data that can further boost the performance of deepARG. In the proposed project, we will curate newly available ARG data and retrain the deepARG models to get the most up-to-date models. We will also improve the usability and portability of the computational pipeline, the downloadable programs, and refine/add user manual and short videos and tutorials.
rg_name: DeepARG: a deep learning approach for predicting antibiotic resistance genes from metagenomic data

description:
The disgenet2r R package contains a set of functions to retrieve, visualize and expand DisGeNET data. The results of the queries can be visualized using different plots, such as heatmaps, barplots and several types of networks. 

In this project we want to expand the applications supported by disgenet2r to the following areas:
-variant interpretation in disease genomics: by annotation of variant/sequencing data files. A new function will be implemented to allow users to read Variant Call Format (VCF) files and annotate them with DisGeNET data.

-pharmaceutical R&D: by supporting federated queries that require integration of several databases available in the Linked Open Data (LOD).

For the latter purpose, we will leverage from the availability of LOD resources in biomedicine such as ChEMBL, Gene Expression Atlas, BioModels, Reactome, UniProt, PubChem, among others. These functions will allow for instance retrieving the druggable targets for a disease of interest or obtaining the biological pathways for a list of disease genes. 

New visualization functions such as lollipops plots for amino acid changes and hive plots for networks will be implemented, among others.

Finally, the code of the package will be re-engineered following the guidelines for package submission to Bioconductor, and submitted to Bioconductor.

This project is for building open source scalable and parallelizable workflow, which will include several pipelines for the analysis of direct RNA (dRNA), complementary DNA (cDNA) and genomic DNA (gDNA) sequencing reads produced by the Nanopore technology. The first pipeline (NanoFluixet) is for raw data pre-processing and mapping; it includes raw data QC, base calling, read QC, de-multiplexing and quality filtering and mapping to a genome/transcriptome. The second pipeline (NanoDirectRNA) is for the analysis of direct RNA sequencing data; specifically, for identification of RNA modification, 3’poly(A) tail length and gene/transcript expression quantification. The third pipeline (NanoIsoform), is for differential expression analysis and identification of novel RNA isoforms using dRNA/cDNA data as input. The fourth pipeline (NanoDNAmod), is for the analysis of DNA modifications in gDNA data. The pipelines are built using the Nextflow framework, which allows incorporating in a modular manner new and updated algorithms, also supporting GPU computing, is distributed with Docker and Singularity containers, and is executable via SGE, LSF, SLURM, PBS and HTCondor batch schedulers and Kubernetes and Amazon AWS cloud platforms. The project also concerns collecting and disseminating experimental data for the benchmarking of the developed software. ​

Genome assembly is the process where the original sequence of the genome is reconstructed from the fragments output by sequencing machines. The MaSuRCA genome assembler is one of the leading open source genome assembly packages. It has been actively developed and supported since 2011.  MaSuRCA supports hybrid assembly of the latest mixed data sets combining inexpensive Illumina data with more costly, but more valuable data from long-read, third generation sequencing technologies such as SMRT sequencing by Pacific Biosciences and Nanopore sequencing by Oxford Nanopore technologies. MaSuRCA has been designed to work in production environment to produce assemblies of genomes ranging in size from a few megabases (bacteria) to tens of gigabases (conifer genomes).  There are 1363 genomes in the NCBI genome database that were assembled by MaSuRCA, including the genomes of turkey, cow, chicken, salmon, bread wheat, and multiple pine trees. 

MaSuRCA is based on the super-reads technique that uses k-mers in Illumina reads to extend the reads to super-reads.  All Illumina reads that extend to the same super-read are replaced by the corresponding super-read. This achieves excellent efficiency and enables MaSuRCA to handle very large data sets, including conifer genomes that are 10 times bigger than the human genome.
rg_name: Continued development of MaSuRCA genome assembler

description:
MathJax is an open-source JavaScript display engine for LaTeX, MathML, and AsciiMath notation that works in all modern browsers. It was designed with the goal of consolidating recent advances in web technologies into a single, definitive, math-on-the-web platform supporting the major browsers and operating systems, including those on mobile devices. It requires no setup on the part of the user (no plugins to download or software to install), so the page author can write web documents that include mathematics and be confident that users will be able to view it naturally and easily.

MathJax includes the ability to generate speakable text versions of mathematical expressions that can be used with screen readers, providing accessibility for the visually impaired. The assistive support in MathJax also includes an interactive expression explorer that helps these users to “walk through” an expression one piece at a time, rather than having to listen to a complex expression all at once, and the ability to “collapse” portions of the expressions to allow a more simplified expresion to be read, and only expanded if more detail is desired.

Matplotlib is a Python 2D plotting library which produces publication quality figures in a variety of hardcopy formats and interactive environments across platforms. Matplotlib can be used in Python scripts, the Python and IPython shells, the Jupyter notebook/lab, web application servers, and four graphical user interface toolkits.

Matplotlib tries to make easy things easy and hard things possible. You can generate plots, histograms, power spectra, bar charts, errorcharts, scatterplots, etc., with just a few lines of code. 

For simple plotting the pyplot module provides a MATLAB-like interface, particularly when combined with IPython. For the power user, you have full control of line styles, font properties, axes properties, etc, via an object oriented interface or via a set of functions familiar to MATLAB users.

MetroNome is a web-based visual data exploration platform, integrating data across sources, including de-identified genomic, transcriptomic, and phenotypic data sets. Users can design and compare cohorts from the combined multimodal data, link back to the sample inventories from which the data was derived, and share data and analysis with outside tools. MetroNome’s interactive visualization and analysis tools are scalable and adaptable, allowing researchers to quickly form and explore novel hypotheses.

MetroNome presently integrates the rapidly growing genomic and phenotypic data sets and analyses generated by the NYGC ALS Consortium. It has become an indispensable central component of the Target ALS Postmortem Core and associated research efforts, which fostered more than 135 different collaborative ALS research projects involving over 100 academic and industry labs in 16 countries, across 4 continents. All biosamples and associated de-identified data are provided openly, without authorship/IP requirements.

The Target ALS Core directors rely on Metronome to (1) analyze the linked multimodal data to form and refine new hypotheses for rigorous testing by the research teams using our resources, and then (2) design optimal biosample and slide sets for each proposed experimental project.

MHCflurry is an open source package for peptide/MHC I binding affinity prediction. It provides competitive accuracy with a fast and documented implementation.

You can download pre-trained MHCflurry models fit to affinity measurements deposited in IEDB or train a MHCflurry predictor on your own data.

Currently only allele-specific prediction is implemented, in which separate models are trained for each allele. The released models therefore support a fixed set of common class I alleles for which sufficient published training data is available (see Supported alleles and peptide lengths).

MHCflurry supports Python versions 2.7 and 3.4+. It uses the keras neural network library via either the Tensorflow or Theano backends.

µManager is an open source software platform for optical microscopy image acquisition: it controls motorized microscopes, scientific cameras, and other equipment and acquires digital images using various techniques.

Optical microscopes for biological research are complex and varied systems, often purpose-built for specific experiments, techniques, or samples, combining equipment from multiple manufacturers. Software plays a central role in these systems, integrating hardware control, automation, and digital data acquisition and processing.

µManager provides both an easy-to-use graphical control interface for microscopists and programming interfaces that enable the creation of novel imaging applications that work with an extremely wide range (approximately 200 families) of available microscope equipment.

µManager development was started in 2005 by Nico Stuurman and colleagues in Ron Vale's lab at UCSF, with the goal of establishing an open platform for the development and dissemination of novel types of microscopy, as an alternative to commercial acquisition software whose functioning cannot easily be inspected or extended by scientists.

Since then, µManager has continued to evolve, with code contributions form researchers as well as equipment manufacturers. Scientists from around the world, as well as small businesses, have used µManager as a software library to develop novel types of microscopy applications.

Python Microscope is a Python package for the control of microscope devices, distributed microscope systems, and automation of microscope experiments. It is designed with the aim of providing an interface to microscopes independent of the hardware details, with a focus on high performance and automation.

To provide independence from specifics of the hardware, Python Microscope defines a standard interface for each microscope device type. Standard interfaces have been defined for cameras, lasers, motorised stages, deformable mirrors, filter wheels, and spatial light modulators. Concrete implementations exist for a range of devices from different vendors.

For best performance with a high number of devices, the interface has been designed with a distributed model in mind. In this model, devices are distributed over multiple computers thus avoiding devices with high resource needs impacting each other, such as the case of multiple cameras at very high frame rates.

Finally, by using the Python programming language, one can easily pipeline measurements with many leading edge machine learning tools, such as those based on TensorFlow. This will significantly enhance the power of the fully automated microscope systems by, for example, enabling AI-controlled diagnostic systems and automated decision making in long-running experiments on live samples.

Based on our SNAP open source code base and deep learning methods that we developed over the last few years, we will develop a software system, called BioSNAP. BioSNAP will provide advanced deep learning methods for analysis of large-scale heterogeneous networks in the biomedical domain in an easy-to-use package.
rg_name: BioSNAP: Deep Learning for Biomedical Networks

description: mixOmics offers a wide range of novel multivariate methods for the exploration and integration of biological datasets with a particular focus on variable selection. Single ‘omics analysis does not provide enough information to give a deep understanding of a biological system, but we can obtain a more holistic view of a system by combining multiple ‘omics analyses. Our mixOmics R package proposes a whole range of multivariate methods that we developed and validated on many biological studies to gain more insight into ‘omics biological studies.

mmtf-pyspark is a Python project for the scalable, interactive analysis and visualization of 3D structures built on Apache Spark/PySpark. mmtf-pyspark is part of a family of "MMTF" projects for 3D structural analysis and visualization, all of which use the Macromolecular Transmission Format (MMTF) for high-performance structure download, parsing, and processing. MMTF combined with parallel in-memory processing achieves over two orders of magnitudes speedup of large-scale 3D structure analysis over legacy applications, enabling for the first time interactive exploration in Jupyter Notebook applications. This enables user to iterative explore new analyses that have not be possible in the past. The NGL viewer application was also developed as part of the MMTF project and has enabled the display of very large molecular machines with millions of atoms in a web browser. It's the default viewer on the RCSB PDB site. Several community members are currently developing the mmtf-cpp framework to enable interoperability with C++ applications, including ROSETTA for protein structure prediction, as well as the SWISS-MODEL repository of about 1.5 million homology models. Several derived projects, mmtf-genomics, mmtf-proteomics, mmtf-workshop-2018 are Jupyter Notebook based reusable workflows and visualization applications.

ModelMatcher is an open matchmaking platform to establish collaborations between scientists and clinicians for rare disease research at a global scale. ModelMatcher is an expansion of the RDMM (Rare Diseases Models & Mechanisms) software, a registry generation and maintenance program package based on Java using the Spring Boot system that is backed by a MySQL database. Although this system has been proven to be effective in collecting and managing valuable data from model organism scientists, additional features need to be implemented to adopt the system for researchers in other scientific fields. In this project, we will add features that are currently not part of the RDMM software that will allow us to collect more accurate information regarding the registrant’s expertise including experimental model systems and organ systems of interest. We will also add features that allow the registrants to take more control over the information that ModelMatcher will use to perform searches and make matches by allowing the users to classify specific genes of interest into “public” and “open-but-secured” categories. The database will be kept fresh by sending out annual e-mails to registrants to confirm their continued interest in contributing to collaborative research on the specific gene they registered for.
rg_name: Optimization of the RDMM program for ModelMatcher

description: Single cell or single nuclei transcriptomic sequencing (also known as single cell or nuclei RNA sequencing or scRNA-seq or snRNA-seq) datasets are growing exponentially in number and size. Although there are numerous tools available to analyse this type of dataset, very limited set of tools are widely accetped and adopted. Also, all of these tools require a fairly good knowledge and experience in unix environment and programming. We propose MONOWIZ, a cloud-based, completely interactive and modular data analytics and visualization platform for scRNA-seq or snRNA-seq datasets which uses the same set of popular tools. We also propose a novel machine learning based analysis algorithm for such datasets. We believe that MONOWIZ will enable biologists to take control of their own datasets and perform, publish and share their results without writing a single line of code. We aim to develop MONOWIZ as an open source platform with the ability to add more tools in future. We also plan to invite community members without any programming background and experience to provide us feedback regarding the usability and performance of the platform.

In-scanner head motion systematically varies with age and diagnosis, and this motion causes bias in morphometric estimates derived from neuroanatomical MRI. There are currently no widely available methods for directly assessing in-scanner motion during acquisition of neuroanatomical sequences. In our preliminary study, we developed a deep learning model to detect in-scanner head motion using raw video data and resting functional MRI images. Using data obtained from healthy controls and employing a deep convolutional neural network, our model was able to detect head motion in all participants with an average accuracy of 96%.

The most immediate and beneficial outcome of our model would be the development of quality assurance tools for imaging centers to quantify the amount of motion during an MRI scan. We propose to develop an interactive website and open source software package to facilitate distribution and rigorous out-of-sample validation of our methods. In addition, we propose to test the existing model by collecting data from a diverse group of subjects. Specifically, twenty participants will be imaged and video recorded during image acquisition. Ground truth head pose estimates will be obtained using functional MRI (fMRI) acquisitions that are acquired simultaneously with in-scanner video.
rg_name: Assess the Amount of Subject Motion During the MRI Procedure

description:
MSstats is a family of open-source R/Bioconductor packages for statistical relative quantification of peptides and proteins in mass spectrometry-based proteomics. MSstats is applicable to

- experiments with arbitrary complex designs (factorial experiments, paired designs, time course)
- data acquired with shotgun DDA, data independent DIA/SWATH, PRM or targeted SRM workflows
- label-free or label-based (e.g., TMT labeling) workflows

The core of MSstats is its state-of-the-art statistical models and algorithms that address technological aspects specific to mass spectrometry-based proteomics. The functionalities include:
- data visualization, normalization, transformation
- detecting differentially abundant proteins, estimating protein abundance, or detecting sites with differential post-translational modifications
- system suitability and quality control for mass spectrometric assays
- characterization of mass spectrometric assays (e.g., limits of detection, dynamic range)
- planning future experiments (sample size calculation for detection of differentially abundant proteins or predictive proteins)

MSstats takes as input a list of identified and quantified spectral features. It interfaces with most currently used open-source and commercial tools (e.g., Skyline, MaxQuant, OpenMS, Spectronaut, ProteomeDiscoverer).

MSstats is widely used in academia and industry (over 50,000 downloads total). The developers hosted, organized and participated in over 40 educational events world-wide, educating biomedical scientists on appropriate statistical practice and use of open-source software in mass spectrometry-based research.

MUMmer is a sequence aligner. Sequence alignment is the most common operation in almost all bioinformatics applications. It is used to compare genomes to measure their evolutionary distance, to assemble DNA and RNA sequences, to quantify RNA expression, to detect genome variations between individuals, etc.

MUMmer is one of the oldest sequence aligner, published in 1999, when genome assembly was just starting and few sequences where available. The original paper correctly foresaw a future where sequences are ubiquitous, even for large genomes.

 MUMmer went through 4 releases, each bringing new features and increase capabilities to handle the larger and more complex alignment problems. MUMmer remains one of the most used sequence aligner, in particular for genome to genome alignment.

The proposed project will keep this very important piece of software up to date and bring further improvements. In addition to strengthening of the code base, new features such as new output formats, increase efficiency on multi-threaded architecture will be added.

We will take particular care to the ease of use and installation of the software, especially for non-computer scientist (e.g., biologist).
rg_name: MUMmer: from early sequencing to modern computational biology

description:
The NaurpaXR virtual reality client written largely in C#. This software allows a user to step into a multiperson simulation and manipulate the dynamics of molecules in real-time.

It has the following features:
. Simulation service discovery
. Real-real time transmission of user positions
. Representation/Overlay controls through JSON.
. Human Interaction controls (e.g fragment or atom selections)

This open-source software project is for the development of the neuroSEE pipeline, which includes the tools ABLE (for Region of Interest segmentation from multiphoton fluorescence imaging) and DeCaF (for extracting spike trains and other physiological event trains from fluorescence time series), as well as an integrated framework for tracking the activity of populations of individual identified brain cells across extended periods of time. Work on the project will include converting several previously developed software implementations of algorithms into Python, and incorporating new features such as the ability to deal with new advances in microscopy technology such as true volumetric imaging.

Newt is a free, web based, open source viewer and editor for pathways in Systems Biological Graphical Notation (SBGN). It was written with a series of libraries and extensions based on Cytoscape.js with utmost customization in mind.

Newt supports nesting pathway content to arbitrary depth to represent molecular complexes and cellular locations with ability to collapse. It also comes with automatic pathway layout, editing and highlighting to enable focus on part of a larger map, and the ability to inspect pathway members for detailed information. We are about to do a public release of new features including support for much faster automatic layout, SIF support, validation of SBGN maps, and advanced diagramming features such as reconnection and resize handles for interactions and relocation of information boxes on biological entities.

Nextflow is a popular scientific workflow manager that enables the development of portable and reproducible workflows. It supports deploying workflows on a variety of execution platforms including local, HPC schedulers, AWS Batch, Google Genomics Pipelines, and Kubernetes. Additionally, it provides support for manage your workflow dependencies through built-in support for Conda, Docker, Singularity, and Modules.

We will develop an efficient software for searching large mass spectral datasets to find known antibiotics and their novel variants. This process, called dereplication, is a crucial need of natural product researchers for (i) avoiding wasteful investment on known molecules, and (ii) finding novel variants of known antibiotics, which could be more effective. In past we have published software for doing this task using brute force search (Mohimani et al., Nature Chemical Biology, 2017, and Mohimani et al., Nature Communications, 2018). However, our previous software are slow for searching billions of mass spectral data currently available in public repositories. For example, searching the entire GNPS repository (1 billion spectra) against the entire PubChem database (80 million compounds) takes ~100 years on 100 CPUs. 
Recently, we have developed novel techniques for searching a large number of mass spectra against theoretical spectra of small molecules using approximate nearest neighbor search (Mongia et al., ICML2019, Computational Biology Workshop). We will apply this technique for efficient identification of antibiotic molecules from billions of mass spectra, and we will release stable software for conducting this search. Our preliminary results show that approximate nearest neighbor search is nearly 100 time faster than the brute force technique.

Celligrate is a project to develop an essential software package for downstream cell type characterization and integration of scRNA-seq datasets. Celligrate includes two customized learning methods: the NS-Forest  (a machine learning-based method for cell type-specific marker gene selection) and FR-Match (a statistical learning method for cluster-to-cluster cell type matching) packages developed by our group, which can be applied to scRNA-seq gene expression matrices with cell cluster membership information. The use of Celligrate extends the utility of the upstream scRNA-seq analysis pipelines to downstream use cases, and ultimately accelerates the growth of knowledge about cell types by integrating results from individual studies.  In this Essential Open Source Software (EOSS) project, we will build a self-contained extensible software infrastructure for cell type matching using NS-Forest/FR-Match and two other established matching methods - scmap for cell-to-cluster mapping and Seurat-CCA for cell-to-cell alignment - to close the gap between individual study scRNA-seq analyses and integrated cell type knowledge extraction. The proposed infrastructure will include independently-implemented analytical software modules, API interface with primary data sources, and compatibility with different programming languages, including Python/SCANPY and R/Bioconductor.
rg_name: Celligrate: essential software for robust single cell RNA-seq cell type integration

description:
NumPy is the fundamental package for numerical and scientific computing with Python. It provides an N-dimensional array data structure and a large set of numerical functions that operate on it. Its array computing concepts – vectorization, broadcasting, indexing, and universal functions (ufuncs) – are used throughout the scientific Python ecosystem, and have also inspired similar libraries in other programming languages. The NumPy API and concepts have been adapted to other Python libraries, such as Dask and Xarray for distributed computing and PyTorch and CuPy for GPU computing. 

NumPy furthermore provides some essential algorithms for numerical applications, such as Fourier transforms, random number generators and linear algebra routines. It also provides many of the utilities and standards for the scientific Python ecosystem: documentation guidelines and the NumpyDoc package, testing tools, and f2py and numpy.distutils for building scientific packages containing compiled code.

NumPy’s is used in all areas of science and engineering, and its user base is estimated to be in the range of 5,000,000 – 15,000,000.

The data generated from both clinical and molecular analysis of cancer patients is getting bigger rapidly, including WGS of tumor tissue, cell free DNA seq from cancer patients’ blood, and single cell sequencing of samples and the clinical metadata associated with these samples.  Optimal use of these datasets requires dimension reduction and the ability for interactive cohort creation and linking to clinical metadata.  Furthermore, comparing and sharing the data with other investigators will be critical as we move forward.  Previously we have created the open source, online tool Oncoscape (http://oncoscape.sttrcancer.io/#/), initially to allow mining of the TCGA molecular and clinical datasets.  We now propose to add enhanced interactive capability to Oncoscape to make it easier to use for clinicians and researchers who are not data scientists. This new version will have additional unique visualization tools, the capacity to record and share all interactive moves made on any dataset, and the ability to create and share raw and processed datasets with other investigators.  The final product will be an open source tool that can be used by clinicians and researchers to manage and learn from the growing datasets related to cancer patients.
rg_name: Oncoscape, a molecular/clinical cancer data visualization tool

description: Variant annotation is fundamental to the goals of genomic medicine and a growing community of geneticists, biologists, physician-scientists, statisticians and computer scientists need access to the latest advances in computational tools and data resources.  OpenCRAVAT is an open source, scalable decision support framework with an extensive catalog of resources to support variant and gene prioritization. It offers a dynamic GUI, allowing users to: install with a single command, easily download tools from an extensive resource catalog, create customized pipelines, run jobs at speeds that exceed current variant annotation API services, and explore results in a richly detailed viewing environment.  OpenCRAVAT is distinguished from similar tools by the amount and diversity of data resources and computational prediction methods available, which span germline, somatic, common, rare, coding and non-coding variants.  The OpenCRAVAT resource catalog is designed to be open and modular to maximize community and developer involvement, and as a result the catalog is being actively developed and growing larger every month.

OpenEBench provides an integrated platform to orchestrate benchmarking activities, from the deposition of reference data to test software tools, to the provision of results employing metrics defined by scientific communities, and the overall accepted standards for software quality assessment. This reference repository offers a general overview for the OpenEBench components including exemplary cases for engaging scientific communities. Each OpenEBench component has their own repository to facilitate their independent organization including contributions beyond the original teams of engineers and researchers.
OMERO is client-server software for managing, visualizing and sharing microscopy images and associated metadata.

OMERO is an open source image data platform used to manage, integrate, analyse, share and publish bioimaging data. It is used by research labs and institutes, biopharma companies and several technology companies as a platform for managing data. A growing set of public resources publish bioimaging data on-line for the benefit of the scientific community with OMERO. The platform includes a relational database (PostgreSQL), an image file repository, search indices, an HDF5 store for tabular analytic data, and a cross-platform API that supports Java, C++, R, Python, web and Matlab clients. OMERO is comprised of an enterprise Java application, OMERO.server and a series of Java and Python clients, including a web client based on Django and several web apps (e.g., OMERO.figure). OMERO uses Bio-Formats to access imaging data and metadata and therefore has been used in a very wide range of applications and imaging domains. We are using OMERO as a foundation of the Image Data Resource (IDR, https://idr.openmicroscopy.org), a curated, public data base of bioimaging data and metadata.

A high performance toolkit for molecular simulation. Use it as a library, or as an application. We include extensive language bindings for Python, C, C++, and even Fortran. The code is open source and actively maintained on Github, licensed under MIT and LGPL. Part of the Omnia suite of tools for predictive biomolecular simulation.

OpenMS offers an open-source software C++ library for LC/MS data management and analyses. It provides an infrastructure for the rapid development of mass spectrometry related software as well as a rich toolset built on top of it. 
It comes with a vast variety of pre-built and ready-to-use tools for proteomics and metabolomics data analysis (TOPPTools) as well as powerful 1D, 2D and 3D visualization (TOPPView).

OpenMS offers analyses for various quantitation protocols, including label-free quantitation, SILAC, iTRAQ, TMT, SRM, SWATH, etc.

With pyOpenMS, OpenMS offers Python bindings to a large part of the OpenMS API to enable rapid algorithm development. OpenMS supports the Proteomics Standard Initiative (PSI) formats for MS data.

Three-dimensional particle tracking velocimetry (3D-PTV) is one of the velocimetry methods, i.e a technique to measure the velocity of particles. 3D-PTV is the three-dimensional method, measuring velocity and velocity gradients along particle trajectories, i.e. in Lagrangian framework, in three dimensions and in time. This is among the few techniques that can measure objects motion in the fluid flow of whatever complexity, three-dimensionality, and unsteadiness. It is possible to obtain the full field of velocity, velocity derivatives along with the Lagrangian acceleration and its spatial derivatives of higher moments. 
The OpenPTV foundation is a collaborative effort of several research groups who joined in order to develop better software for 3D-PTV. OpenPTV is used in a large variety of research areas, from microfluidics to largest wind tunnels, in the physical human cardiovascular system and brain mockups, to tracking violent eruptions of volcanoes. 
The core code written in ANSI C in 1980's is now modernized, compiled and bound with Python providing a flexible GUI, detailed documentation and easy installation for the end-users. The next steps to further democratize the software for the non-professional users is to remove tedious calibration processes and create near real-time result visualization.

OpenRefine is a power tool to clean up messy data. Requiring no knowledge of a programming or query language, it lets users find and fix inconsistencies interactively, match their data to external databases, pull additional data from these, and many other useful operations. The resulting workflows can be extracted and applied on other projects, making them reusable and reproducible.

OpenRefine was originally designed as an Export-Transform-Load tool to populate Freebase, under the name "Freebase Gridworks". It was then briefly a Google product which became an open source project when Freebase was discontinued. Thanks to a grant from the Google News initiative in 2018, integration with Wikidata was developed, making it a tool of choice to import data into Freebase's successor.

Our very active user community runs training workshops about the tool in many universities, newsrooms and libraries. It is easy to get quick and high quality support on our mailing list, StackExchange or Twitter thanks to our committed team of trainers.

Orange (http://orange.biolab.si) is an open-source environment for data science that combines interactive visualizations and machine learning through visual programming. Orange was conceived in 1998 as a C++ and from 2000 as a Python-based machine learning library. Since 2002 we shifted the focus to the graphical user interface with to integrate machine learning and visualizations through visual programming. We aimed to design a powerful data science framework for both experts and novice users to support potentially complex data mining procedures through simple combinations of basic building blocks called widgets. Today, Orange includes over one-hundred-fifty widgets that cover standard data mining tasks of reading the data, preprocessing, modeling, visualization, and evaluation. It follows FAIR principles by supporting automatic saving of the widget state, workflow development, reporting, and workflow sharing. Since 2005, a substantial part of Orange’s functionality focused on data science in molecular biology. Since 2017, we have been designing its add-on for single-cell genomics. It is this add-on, and the repacking of Orange within a comprehensive visual explorative environment for single-cell analytics (http://singlecell.biolab.si) that we would like to focus on the proposed project.

We build the next generation digital libraries for semantic scientific knowledge communicated in scholarly literature. We focus on the communicated content rather than the context e.g., people and institutions in which scientific knowledge is communicated, and the content is semantic i.e., machine interpretable.
Scientific knowledge continues to be confined to the document, seemingly inseparable from the medium as hieroglyphs carved in stone. The global scientific knowledge base is little more than a collection of documents. It is written by humans for humans, and we have done so for a long time. This makes perfect sense, after all it is people that make up the audience, and researchers in particular.
Yet, with the monumental progress in information technologies over the more recent decades, one may wonder why it is that the scientific knowledge communicated in scholarly literature remains largely inaccessible to machines. Surely it would be useful if  that knowledge is more available to automated processing.
The Open Research Knowledge Graph project is working on answers and solutions. The recently initiated TIB coordinated project is open to the community and actively engages research infrastructures and research communities in the development of technologies and use cases for open graphs about research knowledge.
Pandas is an open source, BSD-licensed library providing high-performance, easy-to-use data structures and data analysis tools for the Python programming language.

“Scion” – an open source software for single-cell RNAseq inference of networks and pathway analysis able to handle different types of next generation sequencing data, including single-cell RNA sequencing.

Scion will be based on a previous tool we developed, PathOlogist, with re-written Python code and all its features updated, with several additions; distributed framework for an optimization algorithm, allowing for pathway activity calculation in seconds, handling of bulk-RNAseq, Microarray or scRNAseq data stored in a GEO repository, and availability as a webservice or Python library to allow access to researchers from different backgrounds.  

Scion’s major impact on the research community will be its ability to analyze scRNAseq data; It will include single cell pathway analysis, zero imputation and spatial reconstruction of the original tissue.

We present *AMARETTO as a software toolbox for network biology and medicine, towards developing a data-driven platform for diagnostic, prognostic and therapeutic decision-making in complex diseases. *AMARETTO links diseases, drivers, targets and drugs via network graph-based fusion of multi-omics, clinical, imaging, and driver and drug perturbation data across model systems and patient studies of complex diseases.

The *AMARETTO platform features a modular approach to incorporating prior biological knowledge based on multimodal and multiscale network-structured modeling: (1) AMARETTO learns networks of regulatory circuits - circuits of drivers and target genes - from functional genomics or multi-omics data and associates these circuits to clinical, molecular and imaging-derived phenotypes within each biological system (e.g., model systems or patients); (2) Community-AMARETTO learns subnetworks of regulatory circuits that are shared or distinct across networks derived from multiple biological systems (e.g., model systems and patients, cohorts and individuals, diseases and etiologies, in vitro and in vivo systems); (3) Perturbation-AMARETTO maps genetic and chemical perturbations in model systems onto patient-derived multi-omics networks for driver and drug discovery, respectively, and prioritizes lead drivers, targets and drugs for follow-up with experimental validation; (4) Imaging-AMARETTO maps radiographic and histopathology imaging data onto the patient-derived multi-omics networks for non-invasive and histopathology imaging diagnostics.

PHAST is a freely available and widely used software package for comparative and evolutionary genomics. PHAST supports two main kinds of applications: the identification of novel functional elements through the use of evolutionary conservation; and statistical phylogenetic modeling, including estimation of model parameters, detection of signatures of selection, and reconstruction of ancestral sequences. The package includes eight major programs, plus 15 utilities for manipulating sequence alignments, phylogenetic trees, and genomic annotations. It consists of ~63,000 lines of C code.

We propose to develop an online portal (free access – no registration required) where users can easily create phylogenetic trees of any human protein family annotated with high-quality, and public chemical, structural and functional data. This work will follow two highly popular pilot online interfaces focused on protein families involved in chromatin and ubiquitin signalling: Chromohub (https://chromohub.thesgc.org) and UbiHub (https://ubihub.thesgc.org). Representing protein families as  annotated phylogenetic trees allows a bird's eye view of a target class to rapidly evaluate disease association landscape, literature, structural or chemical coverage, cancer dependancy and other data type. Clicking on any protein on the tree brings additional detail and links to the relevant public repository record or the published article from which the data was extracted. Cell biologists will for example be able to rapidly find high-quality chemical probes for their protein of interest, and medicinal chemists will easily identify structures of phylogenetic neighbours of their targets co-crystallized with chemical inhibitors. Chromohub was cited in 64 articles, UbiHub is used in 76 universities and academic institutes, 9 big pharmas, and over a dozen biotechs. Expanding these popular open-science resources to the human proteome will efficiently serve the chemical biology and drug discovery community.
rg_name: Online portal to explore human protein target classes

description: Phylodynamics is a cloud-based web-app package for the analysis of Primer ID HIV-1 sequencing data to identify recent HIV-1 infections, identify the presence of drug resistance mutations, and define transmission networks all-in-one. We will build the web-app on the GCP based on the current NC pilot project, make significant improvements of the bioinformatics pipelines, extent usage of third-party platforms for data export, and	create user-friendly setup of the web environment. We will also develop a desktop version to comply with HIPPA requirements if needed versus a cloud-app. This project will provide strong support to end the HIV-1 epidemic by contributing to public health interventions.
rg_name: Phylodynamics: A comprehensive bioinformatics tool for HIV-1 recency, drug resistance detection and transmission clustering.

description:
Modern DNA sequencing technology is accumulating massive amounts DNA sequences found in patients with and without disease. For example, in the past 10 years we have accumulated massive libraries of which microorganisms are found in various body sites of patients with and without Crohn's Disease, families with and without autistic children, and more. Making sense of these datasets helps us understand the microbial causes of disease for potential diagnostics, prevention and treatment of these diseases.

How can we analyze such libraries filled with many ATGC character strings indicating the DNA barcodes of microorganisms? We use the most important tool biologists have: evolution. These sequences evolved, and by partitioning an evolutionary tree into lineages associated with disease, a method called "phylofactorization", we're able to find robust classifiers which outperform evolutionarily naïve machine learning tools.

Despite its utility, the GitHub version is in urgent need of attention to maximize its potential in the biosciences. This project proses to (1) make a permanent CRAN package and PyPi library for phylofactorization, (2) integrate phylofactorization into QIIME, the most commonly used point-and-click pipeline for analyzing these datasets, (3) host for phylofactorization-based diagnostics, and (4) build a website for long-term community engagement.

The Pipeline is a collection of services that facilitate the multi-step data processing of the several-thousand tiles per acquisition sample or data-source. The processing may occur in real-time as the data becomes available, offline after acquisition is complete, or a combination of both. Although originally designed to utilize metadata from a specific acquisition process, it has since been generalized to allow processing of additional arbitrary collections of images, although with emphasize towards structured tiling such as 3-D volume microscopy.

It is designed to facilitate a transition from manual processing where processing algorithms in very early stages of development are constantly changing to a dedicated application or system that is fully automated with largely fixed algorithms and stages for processing.  It provides the benefits of a scalable, highly automated data processing pipeline, with real-time visualization and monitoring, allowing substantial flexibility in how the pipelines are constructed, the processes performed at each pipeline stage, and with the expectation of ongoing development of the algorithms within each stage.  It allows the end-user to focus resources on the elements of the research rather than processing infrastructure.

Genotyping arrays enable the direct measurement of an individual’s genotype at thousands of markers. plinkQC facilitates genotype quality control for genetic association studies as described by Anderson and colleagues (2010, doi:10.1038/nprot.2010.116). It makes PLINK's basic statistics (e.g. missing genotyping rates per individual, allele frequencies per genetic marker) and relationship functions accessible from R and generates a per-individual and per-marker quality control report. Individuals and markers that fail the quality control can subsequently be removed to generate a new, clean dataset. Removal of individuals based on relationship status is optimised to retain as many individuals as possible in the study.

Genome-wide association studies (GWAS) have identified thousands of variants robustly associated with complex traits. However, the biological mechanisms underlying these associations are, in general, not well understood. We propose a gene-based association method called PrediXcan that directly tests the molecular mechanisms through which genetic variation affects phenotype. The approach estimates the component of gene expression determined by an individual's genetic profile and correlates 'imputed' gene expression with the phenotype under investigation to identify genes involved in the etiology of the phenotype. Genetically regulated gene expression is estimated using whole-genome tissue-dependent prediction models trained with reference transcriptome data sets. PrediXcan enjoys the benefits of gene-based approaches such as reduced multiple-testing burden and a principled approach to the design of follow-up experiments. Our results demonstrate that PrediXcan can detect known and new genes associated with disease traits and provide insights into the mechanism of these associations.
rg_name: A gene-based association method for mapping traits using reference transcriptome data

description:
PsychoPy is one of the leading packages in experimental psychology and neurosciences. It is extremely easy to use (taught in many udergraduate courses), precise in its timing and measurements, and flexible enough to support a huge range of studies in the field.
After 15 years of open-source volunteer development the project is currently attempting to transition into a fully-funded, but still open source, project. To achieve this we hope to be sustainable on the basis of payments for an experiment hosting service that is currently building its user numbers.
In the meantime PsychoPy would benefit enormously from an injection of funding to provide a smoother user experience and more robust automated testing system. 

(Note that PsychoPy is currently GPL3+ licensed. The Standalone installation of the application will need to retain this license due to its additional dependencies. Potentially we could switch to a dual-license model with a permissive license for the library, and GPL for the compiled application).

We plan to create privacy risk assessment tools and privacy-aware file formats for functional genomics BAM files. These files are usually shared behind controlled access due to anticipated privacy leakages. This creates challenges for reproducibility and open science.

This software will have two modules: (1) A privacy risk-assessment tool to quantify the amount of sensitive information leakage from functional genomics alignment files (SAM/BAM/CRAM). (2) A software suite to convert the alignment files into high-utility, privacy preserving file formats that can be used in downstream analyses. This software will take SAM/BAM/CRAM files as input, generate the leaking single nucleotide variants and transform the input into a privacy-preserving format. It will then calculate the utility loss of the transformation and will report it. 

The primary development language is Python.  For standard coding practices we propose to use black and flake8.  Continuous integration and deployment will be powered by our existing CircleCI configuration. Automatic containerization with docker and singularity will be part of our continuous deployment process.

Cancer immunotherapy has gained significant momentum from recent clinical successes of checkpoint blockade inhibition (unleashing the immune system). More recent efforts have attempted to proactively design personalized cancer vaccines or T cell therapies that will direct a patient's immune system to attack the unique features of their tumor. These immunotherapies rely on predicting which tumor-specific mutant peptides (neoantigens) can elicit anti-tumor T cell immunity.
