Tools are thus needed to allow prediction of checkpoint therapy response and to identify targets for vaccines and other personalized immunotherapies. pVACtools is an in silico sequence analysis toolkit for comprehensive neoantigen characterization.

pyLattice, is an open source library of custom image and data analysis tools, to handle the challenge of big data image analysis brought about by high-content 4D (xzyt) imaging technology such as lattice light-sheet microscopy (LLSM). The current version supports particle detection and tracking of diffraction limited spots in large 4D LLSM datasets. PyLattice provides tools for LLSM input data preprocessing (step 1) such as Jupyter notebook data visualization, movie cropping, and bleaching correction. To ensure accuracy, particle detection (step 2), tracking (step 3), and matching (step 4) are each individually interfaced with Jupyter notebooks to allow the user easy access to intermediate results for quality control. Jupyter notebooks for the final analysis step (step 5) enable quantification, as well as various plotting and 4D visualization functionalities that interface with ChimeraX.

The PylibCZI library is intended to act as a bridge to libCZI provided by Zeiss. libCZI is a vendor-supported ZISRAW/CZI file reading library implemented in C++. PylibCZI was implemented for a specific need the Center of Advanced European Studies and Research (CAESAR) had for a specific project and has not been worked on significantly since. Paul Watkins, at CAESAR, implemented the initial implementation and is very eager to see others contribute to this repo. We have forked the repo and will work there and put in a pull request to merge our changes into the original project. We intentionally chose this pattern in the tradition of open source development. We would rather see this project be enhanced than left behind when it is an excellent place to start and the developer is eager for contributions. That said there is nothing impeding us from creating our own derived child work if we had to. 
The GPL license on the project is a consequence of the libCZI library being released with GPL licensing.

This software is designed to segment, annotate, and analyze time-series image volumes of neuronal dendrites and spines, axons and boutons, vascular networks, and cell bodies. It provides both traditional desktop as well as web based GUI editing. A Python programming API is provided that allows all aspects of analysis and visualization to be scripted as well as extended to meet individual projects experimental needs. Containers are provided to allow easy installation with no programming necessary. The back-end API as well as the front-end GUI interface is fully documented.

The reason this is important is because although there are a number of software environments to analyze single time-point imaging data, there is no simple to use software environment to analyze annotations in the context of longitudinal (e.g. time-series) imaging. Furthermore, the Map Manager GUI is designed to be used by biologists with no programming experience while arbitrarily complex additions can be made using our well documented API.

API documentation: https://pymapmanager.readthedocs.io

GUI documentation: https://mapmanager.net

Available as R/Bioconductor package and Python package. Also available as workflow (Nextflow). QIIME 2 is the most widely used software platform for microbiome analysis. It is open source and free for all use, and aims to be accessible to users spanning the microbiome research ecosystem, including scientists, engineers, and clinicians. QIIME 2 allows users to work from raw DNA sequencing data through publication quality visualizations and statistics. Key features include a plugin architecture, making it an extensible microbiome bioinformatics platform; an integrated, decentralized data provenance tracking system ensuring reproducibility; and complete separation of interfaces from analysis methods, so different interface types are available to users based on their preference (e.g., a command line interface, a Python 3 API, and a GUI are all currently available). 

QIIME 2 users and developers are supported on the QIIME 2 Forum where we strive to provide an open and inclusive environment that fosters learning and improves the quality of microbiome research.

QIIME 2 is an umbrella project for 50 repositories in its GitHub organization, including the QIIME 2 Library. While development efforts for this project will be on the QIIME 2 Library, that is a service in support of QIIME 2 and its community. QIIME 2 should therefore be considered the project supported by this grant.

Qiita is a web application for microbiome analysis, backed by a library of hundreds of thousands of microbiome samples including the complete datasets from the Earth Microbiome Project, American Gut, and other major microbiome projects worldwide. By combining data and a standardized analysis workflow in one place, it provides an interactive platform for rapid understanding of biological and technical factors that lead to microbiome associations, for integrating human and environmental microbiomes, and for relating human clinical microbiome projects to work in animal models.

Leveraging the increased signal to noise ratio and spatial resolution of ultrahigh field 7 T MRI, this project aims to develop quantitative imaging and analysis tools of small vessels in human brain including perivascular spaces (PVS) and penetrating arteries (PA), which play important roles in the etiopathogenesis of cerebral small vessel disease and other neurological diseases.  Specifically, we aim to (1) develop motion-insensitive MRI sequences for imaging PVSs and PAs using ultra-high resolution T2-weighted MRI and phase contrast MRI sequences, respectively, and (2) develop open-source, easy-to-use, automatic and accurate PVS and PA segmentation and quantification software.
 
We will achieve Aim (1) by developing real-time motion correction techniques based on fat navigator images.  In Aim (2), we will achieve the segmentation tasks by developing fully convolutional neural networks.  The PVS quantification will be achieved by clustering analysis of PVS masks segmented from T2-weighted images and geometrical characterization of the clusters. The PA quantification will be achieved by utilizing our recently developed method of model based analysis of complex difference images from phase contrast MRI.

The developed software will provide the neuroimaging community with an invaluable tool to further illuminate the roles of PVS and PA in the etiopathogenesis of neurological diseases.
rg_name: Quantitative Characterization of Perivascular Spaces and Penetrating Arteries in the Human Brain

QuPath is open source software for bioimage analysis. It provides a freely-available, cross-platform, user-friendly, extensible platform that enables biologists, pathologists, image analysts and machine learning experts to work together to maximize the insights we can extract from biological and medical images – including large and complex whole slide images not supported by other open software.

Written from scratch with Java and JavaFX, QuPath is fully scriptable and integrates with other popular open tools, including ImageJ and OpenCV. By combining built-in novel algorithms for common tasks (e.g. cell segmentation) with interactive machine learning and powerful visualization tools, QuPath offers a unique and intuitive platform to rapidly develop and deploy customized and sophisticated image analysis workflows for a wide range of tasks.

Radiomics Enabler® v1 is an ETL (Extract-Transform-Load) for medical imaging. It is a web application which Medexprim developed in collaboration with researchers and clinicians from the Toulouse University Hospital. It allows a user to perform a multi-criteria search on the PACS, filter the results and select the relevant sequences. 

The extraction, de-identification and secured routing of selected images is then entirely automatized. 

The application is functionally structured around research projects, with user rights attached to each project. For each project, users constitute lists of DICOM studies and/or series which are to be batch extracted from the PACS. Each batch has a status associated to it: in preparation, processing, interrupted, complete, in error or archived. 

Radiomics Enabler v2 (end of 2019) will connect to a cloud platform and will send out metrics. This will allow us to have objective metrics on adoption and return this information to our community.

Radiomics Enabler v3 (2020)  will provide cloud collaborative services to serve multicentric projects. The goal is to share results and search criteria, not data.

Rchive is a cloud-based data repository we are building to store curated and reusable genomic data. Rchive is the foundation of the whole AWSomics platform and shared by all the other elements. It is freely available to all users. We continuously and consistently process, format, organize and update Rchive. It currently contains over 15 categories of genomic data and annotation, including about 7,000 sets of GWAS analysis results, over 300 sets of transcriptome data in 8 disease-related collections, millions of gene sets defined by various databases, and so on.

Open source toolkit for cheminformatics and machine learning. 
Written in C++, but accessible from Python, Java, C#. 
Strong focus on code quality, testing, and robustness.
Integrated in various other open-source and commercial tools. 
Active users/contributors in/from industry and academia as well as software companies.
Active and engaged user community (>100 people registered for 2019 User Group Meeting).

Our goal is to build a proof-of-concept end-to-end system that: (1) Runs computational diagnostics on a simple phone interface. We have been implementing a prototype application on the Android platform that doctors in Nigeria will be able to utilize, quickly and efficiently, while on patient calls. This application allows to run a state-of-the-art iterative diagnosis on a simple commodity mobile phone, i.e., doctors can input symptoms and iteratively explore potential diagnosis, including rare conditions they might never been trained for. And, (2) Enables realtime knowledge to upload into the interface, e.g., geographical spreading infectious diseases, complex medical queries on rare conditions, etc. This all happens even when internet coverage (3G and above) is not present. To achieve this we compress and encrypt small queries from the app into 2G text messages that we send to and from a centralized server14.

REDItools comprise a suite of scripts in the portable python programming language and have been conceived to handle massive transcriptome sequencing data through a variety of filters in order to provide accurate RNA editing events. They include three main scripts: 1) REDItoolDnaRNA.py to identify RNA editing candidates by comparing pre-aligned RNAseq and WGS reads in BAM format; 2) REDItoolKnown.py to explore known RNA editing events in RNAseq experiments; 3) REDItoolDenovo.py to detect de novo RNA editing candidates using RNAseq data alone and without any a priori knowledge of genomic information. REDItools include also accessory scripts for filtering and annotating results.

The Shareable, Structured, Semantic Model (S3Model) specifications are based on more than ten years of research and development on computable, semantic interoperability.

The S3Model approach allows subject matter (aka domain) experts to build the data model they need for their application and the shared models are the basis for a model-driven, linked data information management strategy. 

This shareable information model allows data consumers to determine if the data is correct for their needs without imposing requirements on the data capture process.

The core purpose of S3Model is to provide a way to share context across applications either internal or external to organizations. For example, when people communicate with one another, the conversation takes place in a shared environment called “the context of the conversation.” This context allows the individuals to use familiar terms, like the name of a local business or the nickname of a friend to communicate more quickly but without losing accuracy. An S3Model data model provides that context so that applications can automatically understand the data. 

With existing tools, we have modeled hundreds of concepts from other vocabularies such as NIEM, FHIR, HL7v2, NIH-CDE, and OpenEHR in order to show the flexibility and interoperability of the approach.

ALFRED (https://alfred.med.yale.edu) is an open-access, curated, web resource of gene variants on defined human populations. Currently, access to the data in the database is possible only by visiting pages on ALFRED and FROG-kb on the web.  We propose to enhance the usability of ALFRED data by implementing a language and platform independent Application Programming Interface (API) to programmatically retrieve data from the database. The ALFRED RESTful API will be implemented in Java using the JAX-RS and Jersey Framework. We will make the source code available at GitHub and at the ALFRED website. By the end of one year, we will provide RESTful APIs for extracting allele frequency tables in GitHub and ALFRED, as well as detailed documentation for each endpoint with sample calls in multiple programming languages (JavaScript, Perl, Python, R, Java).

libRoadRunner, is an extensible, high-performance, cross-platform, open-source software library for the simulation and analysis of models expressed using the widely used Systems Biology Markup Language (SBML). libRoadRunner is fast enough to support large-scale problems such as tissue models, studies that require large numbers of repeated runs and interactive simulations.

libRoadRunner is a self-contained library, able to run both as a component inside other tools via its C++ and C bindings, and interactively through its Python interface. libRoadRunner uses a custom Just-In-Time (JIT) compiler built on the widely used LLVM JIT compiler framework. It compiles SBML-specified models directly into native machine code making it appropriate for solving extremely large models or large numbers of repeated runs. It is also ideally suited for parameter estimation on large compute clusters. It offers multiple deterministic and stochastic integrators, as well as tools for steady-state analysis, stability analysis, and structural analysis.

In this project, we propose to add the following capabilities: 1) Fast loading of models; 2) Read/Write access to the core of the model via a new API to improve performance even more; 3) Developing an ARM-compatible backend so that it can be exploited on clusters of single-board computers such as the Raspberry Pi.

ROBOKOP (Reasoning Over Biological Objects in Knowledge Oriented Pathways) is a question-answering system that was designed to explore relationships between biomedical entities. ROBOKOP is built upon an underlying Neo4j-based knowledge graph (KG) that provides access to multiple public biomedical data sources that have been semantically integrated. Nodes in the ROBOKOP KG represent entities such as gene, chemical, disease, biological process, cell types, anatomical entities, etc. Edges between nodes provide curated predicates such as “is associated with”, “causes”, or “treat” that explain the association between connected nodes. The ROBOKOP KG currently contains ~500 nodes and ~12 million edges. A researcher-friendly ROBOKOP user interface (UI) allows users to write graphical queries against the KG and receive scored and ranked answer subgraphs. A ranking and scoring algorithm assigns weights to edges in the subgraph, based on publication counts provided by curated data sources and literature co-occurrence provided by  OmniCorp, which is a graph of PubMed entity identifiers that co-occur in abstracts. Users can then browse the automatically ranked answers and view the supporting evidence. In addition, most ROBOKOP components, including the query, ranking, identifier handling, and enrichment capabilities, are exposed as stand-alone services that can be accessed programmatically.

Ribosome profiling, or Ribo-seq, is a powerful technique that uses deep sequencing to monitor  RNA translation in cells (DNA → RNA → translation to PROTEINS). Ribo-seq can be used to improve gene expression profiling, to provide new insights into the mechanisms of protein synthesis itself, and to inform important biological questions. However, the information obtained from Ribo-seq alone is not sufficient, and scientific analyses rely on specially designed methodologies to recover the active translation events from the raw data.

In this work, we propose an unsupervised Bayesian approach to predict translation events from Ribo-seq data. Our method is able to handle de novo translatome annotation by directly assessing the periodicity of the Ribo-seq signal. We use state-of-the-art Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) techniques to estimate posterior distributions of the likelihood of translation of each event. An important feature of Rp-Bp is its ability to incorporate and propagate uncertainty in the prediction process. A second novel contribution is the automatic Bayesian selection of read lengths and ribosome P-site offsets (BPPS). We have provided proteomics- and QTI-seq-based validation of our approach.

SALMON processes RNA-seq samples to extract isoform- and gene-level abundance estimates. These abundance estimates form the input to analyses such as differential gene expression tests that identify which genes are expressed in different levels between two conditions (such as diseased or healthy). SALMON works with both bulk and single-cell RNA-seq samples (the latter supported by its “Alevin” mode). It is very fast (having been derived from the original fast quantifier, Sailfish, by some of the same authors). In addition, it is more accurate than other quantifiers because it has a sophisticated and comprehensive model of sequencing biases that it trains during quantification to automatically match the biases observed in the sample. Salmon is written in C++11/14, has a build system based on automake, and runs on Unix and MacOS.

The da Vinci Research Kit (dVRK) is an “open-source mechatronics” platform, consisting of open-source electronics, firmware, and software, that is being used to control research systems based on the first-generation da Vinci Surgical Robot. The system architecture consists of Linux PC connected to custom electronics (http://jhu-cisst.github.io/mechatronics/) via a high-speed network. The electronics contains a field-programmable gate array (FPGA) to provide direct, low-latency, interfaces between the network and the I/O hardware, which enables researchers to easily implement new algorithms, at any level of control, on the PC.  The software stack implements a component-based design, relying on the cisst libraries (https://github.com/jhu-cisst/cisst) and several Surgical Assistant Workstation (SAW) components available at https://github.com/jhu-saw. The provided GitHub URL (https://github.com/jhu-dvrk/sawIntuitiveResearchKit) contains the dVRK-specific components, examples, and application software. The jhu-dvrk GitHub organization contains other dVRK repositories, including dvrk-ros, which interfaces to the popular Robot Operating System (ROS, www.ros.org), and dvrk-xr, which provides a mixed reality extension based on Unity3D. The current license is a “BSD style license”, adapted from the 3D Slicer project, but is in the process of being changed to an OSI-approved permissive license.

SC3 is a user-friendly method for unsupervised clustering of single-cell RNA-seq data. In addition to identifying natural groupings of cells without prior knowledge, it also finds marker genes and other biologically relevant features to help researchers interpret clusters.

ScanImage is an open-source software application for laser scanning microscopy, electrophysiology, laser scanning photostimulation, and other physiological methods focused on neurobiology.

The software has been previously developed at Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory, Northwestern University , and Janelia Research Campus, with NIH grant support to Gordon Shepherd and Karel Svoboda.

As of 2014, ScanImage is developed and supported by Vidrio Technologies, LLC as both an open-source research resource and as premium software available for sale.

ScanImage is used widely throughout the world and has been essential to the work described in over 720 publications to date.

Scanpy is a scalable toolkit for analyzing single-cell gene expression data. It includes methods for preprocessing, visualization, clustering, pseudotime and trajectory inference, differential expression testing, and simulation of gene regulatory networks. Its Python-based implementation efficiently deals with data sets of more than one million cells.

Scanpy is a scalable toolkit for analyzing single-cell gene expression data. It includes preprocessing, visualization, clustering, pseudotime and trajectory inference and differential expression testing. The Python-based implementation efficiently deals with datasets of one million cells.

scCloud is the first cloud-based framework for analyzing large scale single-cell and single-nucleus RNA-Seq (sc/snRNA-Seq) datasets.  It combines the power of cloud computing with algorithm and implementation improvements to achieve high scalability, low cost, user-friendliness, and support for a more comprehensive set of features.  scCloud supports analysis starting from a variety of input modalities, some not yet supported by mainstream analysis packages, such as Cell Ranger, Seurat, and SCANPY (none of which is Cloud-based), such that users can use it as a single package for diverse data types, all of which share a single cell/nucleus transcriptome as a core readout.  These include: both droplet-based and plate-based sc/snRNA-Seq.  CITE-Seq, which simultaneously measures mRNA expression and the abundance of oligo-tagged surface antibodies at the single-cell level, support for both cell and nucleus hashing, important techniques to reduce batch effects and cell/nucleus profiling costs, using a probabilistic demultiplexing algorithm DemuxEM, and pooled CRISPR screens with scRNA-Seq as their readout, which simultaneously measure the expression of CRISPR gRNAs and mRNAs at the single-cell level.  Other packages currently support only a handful of these datatypes, posing a burden for users.  scCloud is already being used by several atlas building groups.

Recent single-cell Hi-C sequencing (scHi-C) technology provides an unprecedented opportunity to study dynamic chromatin organization, and connects many important areas of genome research, including gene regulation and epigenomics, and allows us to understand the genetic basis of human diseases. However, interpretation of scHi-C data exposes intrinsic data analysis challenges, such as the fact that Hi-C data are essential two-dimensional pairwise measures rather than one dimensional measures as RNA-seq data and ATAC-seq data, and practical data analysis challenges, such as sparsity of contact maps, batch effect, and sequencing noise. To overcome these challenges, we have previously implemented an open source software, scHiCTools, which is the first computational toolbox for analyzing single cell Hi-C data. The toolbox provides commonly used methods for smoothing scHi-C data and projection methods for embedding single cells into a lower dimensional Euclidean space so that users can easily explore and investigate cell-to-cell heterogeneity in terms of their chromatin organization.

scikit-image is the open-source image processing toolkit of Scientific Python. It proposes a collection of algorithms which address the various image processing tasks encountered in science (denoising, segmentation, feature extraction...). scikit-image is application-agnostic and its algorithms accept both two-dimensional and three-dimensional (sometimes n-d) images for compatibility with the various image modalities (microscopy, tomography, MRI, etc.) of science. However, it is a core dependence of many application-specific image processing packages such as CellProfiler or hyperspy.

scikit-image targets a wide community of students, engineers and scientists, many of them self-taught about image processing. An extensive documentation is found on the project website, including some narrative documentation and "getting started" instructions, and also a popular gallery of examples illustrating the use of scikit-image algorithms. 

Since its creation in 2009, scikit-image has been developed primarily by volunteers, using a consensus-based decision-making model. Since 2019, a CZI Imaging Software Fellow, Juan Nunez-Iglesias, is funded to work on scikit-image.  The governance and roadmap of the project is currently made more explicit on https://github.com/scikit-image/scikit-image/pull/3585 and finding a consensus will remain the main way to make decisions in the future.

scikit-learn is a Python library for machine learning built on top of SciPy and NumPy and distributed under the 3-Clause BSD license.
scikit-learn contains models for supervised and unsupervised learning, as well as tools for preprocessing, model selection and evaluation.

It has found wide adoption in research across domains, both in industry and academia, as well as in machine learning applications.

It has emerged as one of the go-to solutions for machine learning in the data science community.

SciPy is a library of numerical routines for the Python programming language that provides fundamental building blocks for modeling and solving scientific problems.  SciPy includes algorithms for optimization, integration, interpolation, eigenvalue problems, algebraic equations, differential equations, and many other classes of problems; it also provides specialized data structures, such as sparse matrices and k-dimensional trees. SciPy is built on top of NumPy, which provides array data structures and related fast numerical routines, and SciPy is itself the foundation on which higher level scientific libraries, including scikit-learn and scikit-image, are built.

Celligrate is a project to develop an essential software package for downstream cell type characterization and integration of scRNA-seq datasets. Celligrate includes two customized learning methods: the NS-Forest  (a machine learning-based method for cell type-specific marker gene selection) and FR-Match (a statistical learning method for cluster-to-cluster cell type matching) packages developed by our group, which can be applied to scRNA-seq gene expression matrices with cell cluster membership information. The use of Celligrate extends the utility of the upstream scRNA-seq analysis pipelines to downstream use cases, and ultimately accelerates the growth of knowledge about cell types by integrating results from individual studies.  In this Essential Open Source Software (EOSS) project, we will build a self-contained extensible software infrastructure for cell type matching using NS-Forest/FR-Match and two other established matching methods - scmap for cell-to-cluster mapping and Seurat-CCA for cell-to-cell alignment - to close the gap between individual study scRNA-seq analyses and integrated cell type knowledge extraction. The proposed infrastructure will include independently-implemented analytical software modules, API interface with primary data sources, and compatibility with different programming languages, including Python/SCANPY and R/Bioconductor.

description: scprep is an all-in-one framework for loading, preprocessing and plotting single-cell data. scprep combines the simplicity of using a framework with the power of working directly with data by providing easy to run methods that work directly with ubiquitous data formats from popular packages numpy, scipy and pandas, allowing the user access to machine learning algorithms developed across the spectrum of data science.

We will design experiments to generate 3D image-based data from 3D cell culture models (e.g., multicellular systems) that are tightly integrated with validation for quantitative profiling and high content screening. Cells in the 3D culture have been shown to grow, interact, and behave more like cells in a living organism than those that are grown in a monolayer. Our aims are to (i) Use eight cell lines with diverse genetic dispositions, culture them in 3D, and image them in 3D. (ii) Develop software to quantify colony organization, nuclear-bound molecular endpoints, and polarity markers. Colony organization is an important index toward high content screening since different mutations lead to the different geometric organization of colonies. Quantifying colony organization will be based on accurate segmentation of nuclear regions, which will leverage and integrate contextual information with the deep learning models. Nuclear-bound molecular endpoints enable proliferation and apoptotic indices to be quantified on a cell-by-cell basis within a colony. And polarity markers enable normal and aberrant colony organization to be classified. Software validation (e.g., nuclear segmentation within a colony) will be tightly integrated with a diverse pattern of colony organization that is driven by mutation landscape of each cell line.
rg_name: High content screening of multicellular systems

description:
1. We will create an extendable compendium of simulated datasets, linked by known parameter shifts to cover a range of models and difficulties for benchmarking tools.  We will start with clustering tools, and then engage the community to extend to trajectory finding, batch/platform integration with varying levels of difficulty, and marker selection that jointly optimize over all classes in a multi-class setting.
2. We will develop guidelines and ontologies to learn statistically-relevant features from real datasets, and adjust the simulations accordingly, for making the latter sufficiently real, and allowing fine-tuning of how closely they match the real data.  We will leverage the emerging test datasets using known mixtures of pure cell types to assess the authenticity of simulated data, while retaining statistical control for testing existing and future technology platforms.  
3. We will stress-test the decisions at every juncture of the workflow, to learn the fault tendencies of alternative algorithmic choices.  We will provide a digital matchmaking system, where a real dataset not only can order its synthetic mimic on-demand, but also can search public datasets for its most similar study - the statistical kindred.  Thus algorithmic decision-making will follow statistical "distance" between datasets rather than biological backstory.
rg_name: Standardized benchmarking of scRNASeq methods with open-source simulations

description:
Transcriptome profiles of individual cells reflect true and unexplored biological diversity, but are also affected by noise of biological and technical nature. This raises the need to explicitly model the resulting uncertainty in any analysis task.  The cohort of existing methods suffers from two key limitations. First, they handle limited subsets of tasks (e.g., clustering but no differential expression) while ideally, a single model of uncertainty should underlie all tasks, thus ensuring consistency and interpretability. Second, most methods cannot scale to the sizes of modern datasets. 

To address this, we developed Single-cell Variational Inference (scVI), a framework for probabilistic analysis of gene expression in single cells. scVI uses variational inference and stochastic optimization of deep neural networks to approximate the parameters that govern the distribution of expression of each gene in every cell, while taking into account nuisance factors such as batch effects. 

scVI enables a robust analysis framework for a range of core tasks (e.g., normalization, harmonization, imputation, dimensionality reduction, sub-population identification, differential expression and cell state annotation) and compares favorably to the state of the art in each and every case. scVI also scales to volumes that are now within reach (over one million cells from multiple samples).
rg_name: Probabilistic representation and interpretation of single cell transcriptomes

description: As described in the proposal epilepsyecosystem.org is a model for an open ecosystem for advancing brain-related biomedical science and engineering. The ecosystem has a current focus on solving major problems in epilepsy, namely epileptic seizure prediction and automated epilepsy diagnosis. Our model is to solve specific problems through sharing of quality data and international crowdsourcing of solutions. Over the long-term we will generalise our approach to other brain-related diseases, however, for the next year we will focus on delivering the 3 open source software modules described in the proposal and work towards solving the proposed problems in epilepsy.

This open-source project is a part of the NIH-sponsored project: a cloud-based system for scalable, privacy-preserving, and interactive immune repertoire analysis in vaccination and infection. The PI Keke Chen is in charge of developing scalable sequence clustering algorithms and lineage analysis tools, where the SCT algorithm plays an important role to quickly summarize large sequence sets. 

The SCT tree is a dynamically growing tree structure that approximately preserve the clustering structures at different levels represented by the internal nodes of the tree (i.e., the summaries). It only needs to scan the dataset once to generate the summary tree. The summary tree can be used for many different downstream tasks, such as clustering and visualization.

The SCT algorithm was just open-sourced recently.
rg_name: Sequence Condensation Tree -  A Component of Cloud-IRseq Workflow

description:
The dramatic drop in sequencing costs has created many opportunities for biologist researchers to generate genomic or transcriptomic sequences from previously understudied organisms. Many research questions related to new models for cancer research, neglected diseases, biodiversity discovery, and improving agricultural productivity require small- or large-scale sequence comparisons. BLAST (Basic Local Alignment Search Tool) is the most established tool for many such analyses.

Unfortunately, BLAST analysis of new data is challenging. There are delays before new data is available on central BLAST repositories such as the NCBI, and only small queries are feasible on such repositories. BLAST can be downloaded and installed locally, but using it is challenging for the majority of biologist researchers with limited experience of command-line interfaces. Finally, commercial software to overcome such hurdles is too costly for many laboratories.

We created Sequenceserver, a free graphical interface for BLAST designed to increase the productivity of biologist researchers performing and interpreting BLAST searches on custom datasets. Our software uses simple algorithms to prevent potential analysis errors, and provides a broad range of text-based and visual outputs to assist biological interpretation. Sequenceserver combines a user-centric design philosophy with sustainable software development approaches and is used by thousands of researchers worldwide.

Seurat is an R package designed for QC, analysis, and exploration of single-cell RNA-seq data. Seurat aims to enable users to identify and interpret sources of heterogeneity from single-cell transcriptomic measurements, and to integrate diverse types of single-cell data.

Chromothripsis Explorer permits to explore the >2,500 tumors included in the Pan-Cancer Analysis of Whole Genomes (PCAWG) project through interactive Circos plots. This project started when we realized that there was no suitable tool for the multi-scale exploration of whole-genome sequencing data. We required such a tool for the curation of the chromothripsis calls (a type of complex rearrangement) we generated as part of our involvement in PCAWG (Cortés-Ciriano et al. Nature Genetics, In Press). Manual curation of mutation calls is still an essential task to dismiss false positive calls. Chromothripsis Explorer is now one of the 5 official PCAWG visualization tools (https://docs.icgc.org/pcawg/). Although this tool has proved very useful to integrate diverse mutation types for one tumor at a time, we now plan to extend it to a more versatile tool, The Cancer Genome Browser, which will include: (i) capabilities to handle multiple samples at the same time, (ii) read-level support for multiple samples using GA4GH-compliant Beacons linked to interactive Circos plots, and (iii) 2D, multi-track visualization of (epi)genomic annotations. Overall, The Cancer Genome Browser will facilitate the curation and interpretation of somatic mutations, which is essential to deliver correct diagnosis for cancer and rare disease patients.

Single-particle IMage Processing Linux Engine (SIMPLE) is an open-source software package for analysis of cryogenic transmission electron microscopy (cryo-EM) movies of single-particles (Single-Particle Analysis, SPA). SIMPLE 3.0 will provide many new features, including a full SPA processing pipeline and a stream SPA platform for informing the data acquisition in real time, using only minimal CPU computing resources. Our stream SPA tool will implement the steps of anisotropic motion correction, automatic power spectrum validation with ice-detection, template/training free particle identification and 2D clustering with automatic particle rejection. SIMPLE 3.0 will additionally feature an easy-to-use web-based graphical user interface that can be run on any device (workstation, laptop, ipad or iphone) and support remote multi-user execution over the network. The new project-based execution model automatically records the executed workflow, facilitates meta-data handling and greatly simplifies usage. Using SIMPLE 3.0, it will be possible to automatically obtain a clean SP data set amenable to high-resolution 3D reconstruction directly upon completion of the data acquisition, without the need for extensive batch image processing.

Sir Isaac is a software package for efficiently inferring dynamical models from noisy and incomplete time series data.  By striving for predictive rather than mechanistic accuracy, the software is able to start from minimal assumptions to produce a dynamical model that approximates training data, the complexity of which is adaptively adjusted as new data become available.  The resulting models are interpretable and are able to predict responses to new dynamical perturbations.   

The mathematical foundation of Sir Isaac consists of ordered hierarchies of dynamical systems that can grow to approximate arbitrary dynamics, including arbitrary nonlinearities and latent state variables.  By limiting the model search space and relying on a variation of Bayesian Model Selection, Sir Isaac inherently minimizes overfitting and efficiently infers dynamical models even in challenging data situations, outperforming all other dynamical inference algorithms. 

Sir Isaac represents one of the very few approaches to dynamical inference that has been shown to work on real biological data.   Recently, it successfully inferred dynamical rules from experimental data describing behavioral dynamics of escape in C. elegans.  The resulting dynamical model produced accurate out-of-sample predictions and hypotheses for neural circuits underlying the behavior.

sktime is a new open source python toolkit for learning with time series. It provides a unified framework for a broad range of time series tasks. The driving philosophy is to provide a single development environment to solve problems that range across numerous scientific disciplines to facilitate the rapid development and evaluation of solutions using state-of-the-art algorithms.  Development of sktime began in 2019, after the modular workflow model was finalised. Currently, it supports advanced time series classification functionality and standard time series forecasting algorithms. As next steps, we will move to complex variants of time series classification (multivariate, unequal length), advanced forecasting functionality, a range of time series annotation algorithms for tasks such as anomaly detection and motif discovery and time to event modelling. We will  apply these techniques to four biomedical case studies: detecting early onset dementia by MEG analysis; exploring sensor data from children hospitalised in an intensive care unit;  finding the relationship between game playing and risk of dementia; and exploring how surgeon motions during operations relate to outcomes. We will achieve this through collaboration with researchers in seven countries and a range of disciplines.
rg_name: sktime: a toolbox for data science with time series

description: Nowadays, supporting human diagnosis in medical fields with computer based automatic systems is a reality. Such systems can find anomalies in patients’ charts synthesizing all kinds of readings, tuberculosis in chest X-rays, lesions in MRI images, etc. The results achieved in medical image analysis among others are tremendous. The supremacy of machine learning with deep neural networks and  automatic feature extraction is uncontestable in these achievements.  However, there is still a major impediment from medical personnel to adopt these methods. Due to the abstract nature of these machine-learning models, for medical doctors, these models act as black boxes that provide an answer for a given input without explaining the answer. The discovery process is hidden from the user and the extracted features lose the rich semantics of the original biomedical features so valuable to biomedical specialists. Therefore, we propose a software toolkit that supports preserving semantics instead of transforming the original input to something, which might make sense only to a machine. It is based on discovering and analyzing the dependencies of these characteristics using General Line Coordinates (GLC). GLC is a solid and already proven lossless mathematical representation of all kind of numerical input data with strong visualization capabilities
rg_name: Visual Knowledge Discovery and Machine Learning Tools for Biomedical Field

description: The Snakemake workflow management system is a tool to create reproducible and scalable data analyses. Workflows are described via a human readable, Python based language. They can be seamlessly scaled to server, cluster, grid and cloud environments, without the need to modify the workflow definition. Finally, Snakemake workflows can entail a description of required software, which will be automatically deployed to any execution environment.

Based on our SNAP open source code base and deep learning methods that we developed over the last few years, we will develop a software system, called BioSNAP. BioSNAP will provide advanced deep learning methods for analysis of large-scale heterogeneous networks in the biomedical domain in an easy-to-use package.

description: Sniffles is our long read based structural variation identification algorithm that significantly improved over other SV callers. Sniffles is currently also the only SV genotyper for long reads enabling a population scale genotyping for ONT and PacBio. To start the analysis, Sniffles estimates the sequencing error rate and other important parameters to automatically adapt itself to the underlying data. This also allows easy usage for non-expert users. The key data structure is a self balancing binary tree that allows a fast access and updated for candidate SVs. Several statistical methods are used to distinguish true from potentially false SVs utilizing the agreement of the individual reads. Furthermore, Sniffles is the only SV caller that can identify adjacent and more complex SVs that have been associated with human diseases such as blood clotting disorders. Sniffles has already been used by thousands of people to detect SVs and is the recommended methods for SV calling based on long read data.

We will extend an algorithm for a comprehensible  graph summary of ontology-based annotations to biological entities (such as genes)  to other ontologies (notably the Gene Ontologies). This will be employed at the Alliance of Genome Resources Central Portal as well as individual model organisms daabases such as WormBase.

SoS Notebook is a Jupyter kernel, with frontend extensions to both classic Jupyter and JupyterLab, designed for interactive multi-language data analysis. The SoS kernel serves as the master kernel for all other Jupyter kernels and enables the use of multiple kernels in one notebook. With assistance from multiple language modules (sos-bash, sos-r, sos-matlab, etc), SoS Notebook allows data exchange among live kernels of supported languages.

The frontend extension to classic Jupyter adds a console panel for the execution of scratch commands and display of intermediate results and progress information, and a number of shortcuts and magics to enhance interactive data analysis. Working closely with the JupyterLab team, these features have been ported to JupyterLab, either in the sos extension or as core features of JupyterLab. 

SoS Notebook also serves as the IDE for the SoS Workflow that allows the development and execution of workflows from Jupyter notebooks. This not only enables easy transition of scripts developed for interaction data analysis to workflows running in containers and remote systems, but also the creation of scientific workflows in a format with narratives, sample input and output.

SPAdes – St. Petersburg genome assembler – is an assembly toolkit containing various assembly pipelines. Started as a highly specialized tool for single-cell MDA-amplified genomic data, SPAdes quickly turned into useful tool for many generic genome assembly projects.
Over the years SPAdes team strived to provide a universal user-friendly tool that "just works" and continued the development, maintenance and improvement of the tool extending its area of applicability as well working on gradual improvement of the performance, memory consumption, computational efficiency, etc.
These days SPAdes could utilize many different genomic, metagenomic and transcriptomic data types in any order and includes special modes tuned for the huge variety of different assembly tasks.
SPAdes is available from many cloud-based platforms such as Illumina BaseSpace, EMBL-EBI MGnify among the others.

Spaniel is an an R package providing a framework for analysing and sharing Spatial Transcriptomics data. Spaniel provides methods for thorough quality control, visualisation and pre-processing of the data. It uses two pre-existing S4 objects designed for single cell analysis, namely Seurat object and SingleCellExperiment object, providing strong potential for integration of and with other single cell datasets. Spaniel also provides a Shiny app which allows results to be shared in an interactive manner.

The Spectra package provides efficient and flexible infrastructure to store, manage and process raw mass spectrometry (MS) data, namely spectra of any MS level. It relies on a set of different backends that all share a common interface. Users and developers will be able to manipulate their data independently of the location of their data, i.e. whether it is (fully) stored in memory, on disk (as native raw data files), in a database (such as HDF5 or SQL-based) or remote (for example available on the Bioconductor ExperimentHub cloud). With larger amounts of raw data available remotely, dedicated backends will also support remote computations, following and adapting similar efforts already explored within the Bioconductor project. In addition to standard MS data processing functionality such as smoothing, peak picking and data annotation, the package also allows spectra comparison and clustering. The goal of this package is to enable users to (1) develop automated and high-throughput pipelines, (2) understand and debug data and their processing step by step and (3) develop and compare novel data processing techniques using a flexible and efficient programmatic interface. This EOSS project will focus specifically on a cloud backend and integration with the Bioconductor ExperimentHub infrastructure.

Spinal Cord Toolbox (SCT) is a comprehensive, free and open-source software dedicated to the processing and analysis of spinal cord MRI data. SCT builds on previously-validated methods and includes state-of-the-art MRI templates and atlases of the spinal cord, algorithms to segment and register new data to the templates, and motion correction methods for diffusion and functional time series. SCT is tailored towards standardization and automation of the processing pipeline, versatility, modularity, and it follows guidelines of software development and distribution. Preliminary applications of SCT cover a variety of studies, from cross-sectional area measures in large databases of patients, to the precise quantification of MRI metrics in specific spinal pathways. SCT is bringing together the spinal cord neuroimaging community by establishing standard templates and analysis procedures, thereby fostering the reproducibility of scientific results.

spm1d is an open-source Statistical Parametric Mapping software package for analyzing smooth, one-dimensional multivariate continua, including especially the 3D joint angle time series and 3D force time series that characterize human movement. It is currently used by over 2000 researchers worldwide for analyzing clinical movement disorders, assessing rehabilitation effectiveness, and quantifying sports performance. It uses random field theory to generalize hypothesis testing and all other statistical techniques to the domain of one-dimensional multivariate continua .  This project is young (only about five years old), and has only one main developer (the applicant). While there is a prospective user pool of well over 100,000 individuals, the primary barriers to wider adoption have been (a) its interface: most clinical users cannot program, and spm1d currently supports only text-based programming, (b) statistical versatility (i.e., support for arbitrary experimental designs and data problems): normal academic funding streams will not support this infrastructure development, (c) documentation: clinical users often have only basic statistical knowledge, and need better eLearning resources to realize spm1d's capabilities, and (d) fragmentation: five other relevant GitHub repositories, representing individual academic papers, are not yet integrated with the parent package.

Contains the source code and database models for the SQAN Application Programming Interface (API), Web Portal User Interface (UI), and modules pertaining to data/metadata retrieval, extraction, translation, logging (ETL) and executing quality control algorithms.  Upon deployment this suite of tools will retrieve and harvest metadata from the data transfer service, compress and store the metadata in a database, and initiate quality control tests against new data and as requested against existing data.  The API provides access control and mediates between the UI and other systems.  The UI allows researchers and technologists to directly inspect the metadata on millions of images, and the ability to rapidly identify QC issues in acquired data with informative alerts and visual indicators.  This project follows the MEAN stack template, consisting of a MongoDB database, ExpressJS and AngularJS frameworks for the API and UI respectively, and executed via the Node.js runtime.  SQAN is based off the RADY-QC project, developed in a partnership between Indiana University's Scalable Compute Archive (IUSCA) team and the RADY Imaging Center (Indianapolis).

BioModels is a repository of mathematical models of biological and biomedical systems. It hosts a vast selection of existing literature-based physiologically and pharmaceutically relevant mechanistic models in standard formats. BioModels widely used among the systems modelling scientists across the globe, as we provide Findable Accessible Searchable Reusable (FAIR) data sharing platform for the modellers. Our mission is to provide the systems modelling community with reproducible, high-quality, freely-accessible models published in the scientific literature.

SR-TESSELER is an open-source segmentation software for the quantification of 2D single-molecule localization microscopy data. Developed in C++, it uses Voronoi tessellation constructed from the coordinates of localized molecules to add features to those localizations. Improved interaction and manipulation of the SMLM data is achieved thanks to a direct vectorial rendering of the localizations and Voronoi cells.

SR-TESSELER allows precise, robust and automatic quantification of protein organization at different scales, from the cellular level down to clusters of a few fluorescent markers. It is insensitive to cell shape, molecular organization, background and noise, allowing comparing efficiently different biological conditions in a non-biased manner, and perform quantifications on various proteins and cell types.

SSM is an open-source software project for building and applying state space models to the large-scale datasets now common in biology.  SSM includes classic models, like hidden Markov models and linear dynamical systems, as well as modern variants, many of which build on recent advances in deep learning.  These models are aimed at uncovering low dimensional states underlying high dimensional data and explaining how these states evolve over time.  As such, they are invaluable tools for reasoning about complex biological processes.

STAR (Spliced Transcripts Alignment to a Reference) is an ultrafast, versatile and feature-reach RNA-seq analysis software. Owing to ultra-fast speed and high accuracy, STAR has become the most prevalent RNA-seq aligner in transcriptomic studies. STAR performs spliced alignment of RNA-seq reads to the reference genome, discovers annotated and novel splice junctions, and detect fusion transcripts.

    To mitigate bottlenecks and compatibility hurdles, many post-mapping tools have been integrated directly into STAR, including sorting of the BAM files, signal (wiggle generation), variant detection, and gene quantification.

    STARsolo is a comprehensive ultra-fast turnkey solution for analyzing droplet single-cell sequencing data (Drop-seq, 10X, etc.), built into STAR suite. STARsolo inputs raw FASTQ reads and performs (i) demultiplexing of Cell Barcodes; (ii) sequencing error correction and collapsing of UMIs; (iii) mapping the reads to the reference genome using; (iv) quantification of per-cell gene expression. The above steps are performed simultaneously resulting in massive (5~10 fold) boost in processing speed.
The STARsolo output is designed to be a drop-in replacement for 10X CellRanger gene quantification output. STARsolo is also capable of detecting alternative and novel splicing, novel transcription termination sites, unannotated transcript/genes, and fusion junctions in scRNA-seq data.

StarryNite/Acetree are cell tracking and lineage editing tools used primarily, though not solely in the C. elegans community to trace and interact with embryonic cell lineages. Developed by Zhirong Bao while a postdoc in Bob Waterston’s lab at the University of Washington the software has been used, maintained and updated for around 15 years with efforts focussed at MSKCC for the past decade. It is the dominant tool for cell tracking in the C. elegans embryo and regularly used in around a dozen labs in support of projects like dynamic single cell gene expression and the WormGUIDES neuronal outgrowth atlas. 

StarryNite, written in Matlab, provides tracking for fluorescently labeled nuclei.  Tracking combines image processing and classical machine learning to provide high accuracy on dense cells in limited (axially and laterally) resolution images. Acetree is a Java-based interface for curating and exploring results superimposed over images or as an abstract 3D model with detailed control over model coloration. It includes tools for editing, bookmarking and annotating events. Both tools will work with arbitrary data, but provide logic for automatically assigning canonical C. elegans names to cells and a variety of other convenient features for navigating C. elegans embryos.

STREAM(Single-cell Trajectories Reconstruction, Exploration And Mapping of omics data), is an interactive pipeline capable of disentangling and visualizing complex branching trajectories from both single-cell transcriptomic and epigenomic data. It also allows for automatic developmental-trajectory-related marker gene discovery and visualization. 
STREAM can take as input both single cell transcriptomic and epigenomic data. It reliably reconstructs trajectories and pseudotime in both simple bifurcation or complex branching situation without the need of prior knowledge about the structure or the number of trajectories

STREAM provides a mapping procedure, which permits reusing a previously inferred principal graph as reference to map new cells not included in the original fitting procedure (Currently it's only supported at command line interface https://github.com/pinellolab/STREAM)
STREAM provides analytical tools for potential marker genes (or k-mers) of different types: diverging genes, i.e. genes important in defining branching points that are differentially expressed between diverging branches, and transition genes, i.e. genes for which the expression correlates with the cell pseudotime on a given branch.
STREAM provides both single-cell-level and density-level visualizations of cells and gene expression patterns for inferred trajectories. Specially, STREAM proposed a novel visualization, called the stream plot, which is useful to study subpopulation composition and cell-fate genes along branching trajectories.

1. We will create an extendable compendium of simulated datasets, linked by known parameter shifts to cover a range of models and difficulties for benchmarking tools.  We will start with clustering tools, and then engage the community to extend to trajectory finding, batch/platform integration with varying levels of difficulty, and marker selection that jointly optimize over all classes in a multi-class setting.
2. We will develop guidelines and ontologies to learn statistically-relevant features from real datasets, and adjust the simulations accordingly, for making the latter sufficiently real, and allowing fine-tuning of how closely they match the real data.  We will leverage the emerging test datasets using known mixtures of pure cell types to assess the authenticity of simulated data, while retaining statistical control for testing existing and future technology platforms.  
3. We will stress-test the decisions at every juncture of the workflow, to learn the fault tendencies of alternative algorithmic choices.  We will provide a digital matchmaking system, where a real dataset not only can order its synthetic mimic on-demand, but also can search public datasets for its most similar study - the statistical kindred.  Thus algorithmic decision-making will follow statistical "distance" between datasets rather than biological backstory.
rg_name: Standardized benchmarking of scRNASeq methods with open-source simulations

description: Tetrad is a desktop application written in Java which performs graphical causal modeling and discovery from background knowledge and data. Tetrad provides state-of-the-art causal discovery methods through a user interface that does not require programming knowledge.  As described in the current proposal, we are using the algorithms and user interface elements implemented in the Tetrad project to build a Causal Discovery App for Cytoscape. To construct a Causal Discovery Tool for Galaxy, we will use our existing command line tool that wraps the Tetrad functions.

Antigenic peptide recognition by T cell receptor (TCR) plays a key role in the fight against pathogens and cancers, in the development of vaccine, and in the study of pathogenesis of many auto-immune diseases. Measuring the tremendous amount of possible pairings between TCRs and peptides were limited by the available low-throughput experiment technologies previously. We and others have developed technologies for high-throughput pairing of TCR sequences with their binding antigenic peptides, which facilitate the mechanistic study of T cell mediated disease pathogenesis. Although several tools that emphasize various aspects of TCR antigen specificity analysis have been developed, there lacks a computational platform that is specifically designed for gathering, visualizing, and mining those valuable data. Here, we propose an informatics platform that integrates three parts: a web-based portal as data repository on paired TCR/binding-peptides records, a toolset integrating existing analysis algorithms for constructing a knowledge graph of TCR-antigen specificities, and a new algorithm for discovering peptide specific and/or cross-reactive TCR binding motifs. Together, these open source tools will facilitate studies of TCR specificity and cross-reactivity, which will be the first step toward understanding the black box of T cell repertoire that is vital to human health.
rg_name: Knowledge graph and data mining tools for TCR-antigen specificity analysis

description: CryoEM is now a powerful tool for determining the atomic structures of biological macromolecules in solution. The major task of single-particle cryoEM is to estimate a set of parameters for each input particle image to reconstruct a three-dimensional density map. With the increasing requirements for high resolution and automation in large-scale applications, a robust reconstruction program with reliable and accurate parameter estimation is becoming more and more important, especially, in the presence of images with various qualities. Under this background, we had developed a particle-filter algorithm for cryoEM as a sequential Monte Carlo method for high-dimensional parameter estimation. Based on the particle filter, we had established a general Bayesian framework for future cryoEM development, and implemented in a newly developed program named THUNDER.

This repository provides differentiable layers integrated with PyTorch, that compute:

1. Conversion between dihedral angles of a protein to coordinates of atoms. Backbone protein model is implemented on CPU and GPU and full-atom model is currently implemented on CPU only

2. 3D Protein representation as density maps of atomic types of a molecule (GPU only implementation)

3. Loss function, defined on a set of atoms, namely minimum RMSD (CPU and GPU implementations)

5. VolumeConvolutions for protein-protein docking. This layer computes convolutions between equal volumes using cuFFT (GPU only)

6. Translation and rotation of atomic structures (CPU) and volumes (GPU).

Also this repository contains additional non-differentiable functions, that are useful for protein structure prediction and protein-protein docking, such as PDB loading, saving density maps as *.xplor files, generating uniform random rotations and others.

To protect humans and the environment, the safety assessment of new innovative pharmaceuticals or agricultural chemicals relies on animal testing for regulatory approval. Many industrial companies and regulatory agencies are advancing new toxicogenomic methods (intersection of safety and genomics) to reduce the use of animal testing and improve the accuracy of these safety predictions. In partnership with Eli Lilly and Corteva Agriscience, the Indiana Biosciences Research Institute (IBRI) has taken these partners’ internally-developed toxicogenomics analysis methods and developed a Collaborative Toxicogenomics (CTox) platform that is now openly available through a cloud-based website (March 2018) and placed the code base in open source on GitHub (April 2019). 

This collaboration was initiated to not only meet the needs of the collaborators but to provide this platform to a broader scientific community by making it available through an open source license to enable broad community-based use, extensions, and improvements. This proposal seeks funding to assist these open source objectives by closing gaps in user documentation and tutorials, platform deployment documentation, refactor the existing code to assist other contributors to add new analysis modules, and to host an inaugural meeting of our diverse and growing User Group to help shape the CTox platform’s future.

Web-based genomics data access, analysis and visualisation application, originally developed for toxicogenomics but now usable for general multi-omics data analysis.
The tool integrates a hybrid database s(RDF + key-value store) with various GUI analytics functions, including tabular data display with contextual information, network analysis and visualization, ranking of aggregated samples, and integrated mRNA-miRNA analytics. It was originally developed to study the "Open TG-GATEs" toxicological mRNA microarray dataset, but can now be applied to a wider variety of data. Command line tools for data management and a separate data management UI also exist.

TransPrise - an efficient deep learning tool for prediction of positions of eukaryotic transcription start sites. TransPrise offers significant improvement over existing promoter-prediction methods. Using a computer equipped with a graphics processing unit, the run time of TransPrise is 250 minutes on a genome of 374 Mb long.

RiboSeq.Org is a web portal providing access to the tools for the processing, analysis and visualization of ribosome profiling data. It consists of three resources: GWIPS-viz, RiboGalaxy and Trips-Viz. GWIPS-viz automatically processes publicly available ribosome profiling data and aligns it to the sequences of genomes available in GWIPS-viz. The users are then free to download these data as well as use GWIPS-viz browser for graphical exploration of the alignments in conjunction with auxiliary information provided in GWIPS-viz, which includes major annotations, phylogenetic conservation, mappability, etc. as well as data metainformation and data quality characteristics (using RUST). RiboGalaxy is an instance of Galaxy tailored for ribosome profiling data processing and analysis, it provides Galaxy GUI interface for the command-line tools developed for these purposes. Trips-Viz is an interactive computational environment that enables users to analyse public as well as private ribosome profiling data aligned to reference transcriptomes in a secure collaborative manner. Trips-Viz provides a large range of graphical tools for exploring global properties of translatomes and of individual transcripts. It enables analysis of aligned footprints to evaluate datasets quality, differential gene expression detection, visual identification of upstream ORFs and alternative proteoforms. Trips-Viz is the main focus of the current proposal.

The goal of the UDM Toolkit project is to provide a set of software tools that will facilitate the adoption of the UDM file format-an open, extendable and
freely available data format for the exchange of experimental information about compound synthesis and their testing.  The UDM file format and the underlying data model deliver higher quality experimental data and ease
collaboration across life science organisations.  This will underpin the growing need for high quality and accessible (FAIR) data in AI & ML workflows by delivering higher quality research across life science and health.

Unified Medical Language System® (UMLS) is curated by National Library of Medicine, National Institutes of Health. Since 1986, UMLS integrated 214 disparate vocabularies and ontologies (sources), robustly spanning biomedicine, into a simple unified structure. UMLS is the most complete unified semantic graph of biology and medicine having tremendous potential beyond individual sources. However, the UMLS distribution is non-intuitive, and cumbersome in relational form. We have demonstrated UMLS graph coherence across all sources and efficient navigation by ingesting UMLS into one graph of nodes and edges (UMLS-Graph) and deploying a visual explorer free online (at guesdt.com). Our API enables full capabilities because it is a single AWS Gateway API that injects Cypher queries into the Neo4j database. The deployed UI reveals expansive semantics and is used for ontology, term, code, and concept selection, synonymy in search applications, source tree extraction, and more. This funding request seeks to mature UMLS-Graph from successful experiment, to professionally managed open project. We will code and document UMLS ingest options, expose robust open APIs, communicate useful paths and features, and release modular UI components. Funding will support community effectiveness and efficiency with ontology data, specifically to analyze, visualize, and robustly integrate semantics into biomedical applications.
FreedomScope is an open source hardware and software project for minimally invasive recording of neural activity in-vivo.

Virtual Scanner is an end-to-end hybrid MR simulator/console designed to be easily accessible, modular, and supported by open-source standards. The project is a response to one of the ISMRM 2019 Junior Fellow Challenges (https://www.ismrm.org/2019-junior-fellow-challenge/africa/). It runs on a browser and serve both educational and research purposes. All backend code is in Python and the frontend is developed using the FLASK framework.

Virtual Scanner consists of two modes: in Standard Mode, a console-like GUI allows users to perform virtual scans and conduct basic analysis; in Advanced Mode, modular simulation/analysis of the entire MR signal chain may be performed. At the moment, three pages (Register, Acquire, and Analyze) have been implemented in Standard Mode and two (RF transmission, RF reception) in Advanced mode. 

We expect Virtual Scanner to be a valuable open-source MR system simulator that will help both advance research at our lab and around the world as well as support MR education in under-served areas.

Nowadays, supporting human diagnosis in medical fields with computer based automatic systems is a reality. Such systems can find anomalies in patients’ charts synthesizing all kinds of readings, tuberculosis in chest X-rays, lesions in MRI images, etc. The results achieved in medical image analysis among others are tremendous. The supremacy of machine learning with deep neural networks and  automatic feature extraction is uncontestable in these achievements.  However, there is still a major impediment from medical personnel to adopt these methods. Due to the abstract nature of these machine-learning models, for medical doctors, these models act as black boxes that provide an answer for a given input without explaining the answer. The discovery process is hidden from the user and the extracted features lose the rich semantics of the original biomedical features so valuable to biomedical specialists. Therefore, we propose a software toolkit that supports preserving semantics instead of transforming the original input to something, which might make sense only to a machine. It is based on discovering and analyzing the dependencies of these characteristics using General Line Coordinates (GLC). GLC is a solid and already proven lossless mathematical representation of all kind of numerical input data with strong visualization capabilities
rg_name: Visual Knowledge Discovery and Machine Learning Tools for Biomedical Field

●Required GPU memory > available GPU memory: 
●Required GPU memory > available CPU memory: 
●Required processing memory > available CPU memory: 
●Better detection of GPU and openGL capabilities: 

These improvements will require adding new capabilities into VTK for processing a large volume into a pyramidal representation and store it on disk, implement a volume rendering mapper able to load on demand the correct part, and updating Slicer volume rendering module and IO infrastructure. Also a rendering issue identified when enabling partitioning for texture streaming. We will investigate how to best set partitioning size automatically and will update the Slicer volume rendering module accordingly.

Web-application generator system; system for rapidly creating web-based applications in a semi-automatic matter through the generic system outlay. This system is, at first, only intended for the development of bioinformatics related applications. A computation or algorithm can be integrated in the application by 'linking' the web-application with an external API.

Protégé is the de facto standard toolset that scientists in biomedical informatics, and in many other disciplines, use to create ontologies. The system has evolved radically over the last two decades, and it is currently available in two implementations: (1) Desktop Protégé—a full-fledged OWL ontology editor, implemented as a Java Swing application, and (2) WebProtégé—a collaborative ontology editor for the Web. Both platforms support the latest version of the Web Ontology Language (OWL 2), which is a World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) recommendation and the latest standard in ontology languages. WebProtégé comes with a simplified user interface specifically targeted to biomedical ontologies. This interface was designed using an innovative approach based on empirical evidence of commonly used constructs. It also offers various collaboration features, including discussion threads and watches, supports change tracking for keeping abreast of multi-user edits, and offers visualization for ontology comprehension.

Protégé remains the leading, scalable open-source technology for ontology engineering, with more than 300,000 registered users, and almost 60,000 new registrations since 2015 alone. According to Google Scholar, more than 33,000 scientific publications mention Protégé as enabling technology for the underlying research.

The workflowr R package helps researchers organize their analyses in a way that promotes effective project management, reproducibility, collaboration, and sharing of results. Workflowr combines literate programming (knitr and rmarkdown) and version control (Git, via git2r) to generate a website containing time-stamped, versioned, and documented results. Any R user can quickly and easily adopt workflowr.

XTK is an established library for web-based biomedical visualization. Developers can create interactive 3D renderings of common medical imaging file formats with very little lines of JavaScript code. The resulting visualizations do not require any software installation or data conversions and run fully in the browser or in Jupyter notebooks. XTK offers rich functionality to render and interact with image volumes, meshes, fiber tracks, and many more.

ZENBU is a web-based analysis and visualization system developed as part of the FANTOM (Functional Annotation of the Mammalian Genome) consortium projects to help interpret the ever-increasing amount of genome, transcriptome, and epigenome data produced by next-generation sequencers. Gaining biological insight from such data remains a formidable challenge, especially as huge amounts of transcriptome data are produced for individual human cells as part of the Human Cell Atlas.

ZENBU was designed to support large-scale transcriptome projects such as FANTOM5, allowing users to combine and visualize thousands of experiments on demand. Data processing and complex views are achieved by a scripting system consisting of data transformation and analysis modules, giving users optimal control.

ZENBU has proven its value in the FANTOM5 project, where it was used by most consortium members to inspect and interpret transcriptome data in a genome context. More recently, support for building supplementary websites showing analysis results for data already loaded in ZENBU was added to the system.

ZENBU is freely available as a web service at http://fantom.gsc.riken.jp/zenbu/. ZENBU is written in C++ for server web services and in JavaScript for client-side visualization. ZENBU can also be installed locally from the open-source source code obtainable from github.
